<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Marines Leader Wants More 'Fun' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- By a reputation earned in 223 years as  
America's seafaring soldiers, Marines are tough. What troubles 
their new leader, Gen. James L. Jones, is that their lives can be 
tough, too -- too tough, considering that one of the military's 
biggest problems is keeping people in uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus Jones is quick to assure his troops that while military  
service is demanding, it need not be grim. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's OK to have fun in the Marine Corps,'' he told a group of  
straight-faced Marines in Stuttgart, Germany, at the outset of his 
inaugural troop tour shortly after becoming commandant July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Fun for Jones means appreciating the unique rewards of military  
service, bonding with fellow Marines. And it means being allowed to 
do your duty without being burdened by overly rigid bureaucracy. It 
means getting field assignments -- like stabilizing the peace in 
Kosovo -- that make a difference. 
</P>
<P>
	On that four-country trip Jones spelled out his top priorities:  
moving more Marines out of noncombat jobs into the fighting, or 
``operational,'' force; improving the quality of life for Marines 
and their families; and instilling more tolerance for mistakes 
while maintaining the Corps' high standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to allow people to grow, learn from their mistakes  
and tolerate those human imperfections,'' Jones said. ``I like to 
say we are an imperfect people working in an institution that tries 
to be perfect. That is a noble thing ..., but you have to realize 
there is no perfect. We're human.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to a Marine anti-terrorism unit in Naples, Italy, Jones  
said that in his four years as commandant, Marines will find 
themselves pulled through fewer ``knotholes.'' By that he meant 
that Marines will be able to advance their careers with fewer 
reviews and other stressful administrative demands. 
</P>
<P>
	He wants Marines to feel part of the ``ownership'' of the Corps,  
with a say and a stake in its future. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing we do in the Marines is what you do,  
not what I do,'' he told a few dozen Marines in a maintenance 
shelter at Aviano Air Base in Italy, as pairs of F-16 fighters 
roared overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 55, got his dream job on the recommendation of Defense  
Secretary William Cohen, who has known Jones for two decades. Cohen 
made Jones his senior military assistant when he became defense 
chief in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of a person that I've encountered over the years  
who has more compassion for people and a greater willingness to 
understand the challenges that confront them than Jim Jones,'' 
Cohen said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said he expects Jones, a 32-year Marine veteran, to press  
for evolutionary, not radical, change. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a Marine Corps that is working,'' the defense  
secretary said, thanks to predecessors like Gen. Charles Krulak, 
who retired as commandant in June after four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Kansas City, Mo., Jones grew up in France where his  
father worked for International Harvester after leaving the Marine 
Corps. He returned to the United States for his senior year in high 
school and then attended Georgetown University's School of Foreign 
Service. He was commissioned a second lieutenant in the Marine 
Corps in 1967 and was sent to fight in Vietnam that same year. 
</P>
<P>
	As commander of an understrength rifle company in Vietnam in May  
1968 near Khe Sanh, Jones and his men made a heroic stand against a 
North Vietnamese onslaught that lasted 12 hours. For his valor in 
what he calls a ``definitive moment'' as a Marine, Jones was 
awarded the Silver Star Medal. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a 12-hour period those Marines taught me more about what  
the Corps stands for than any other experience of my life,'' Jones 
said at his change-of-command ceremony in Washington on June 30. 
Members of that rifle company, some of whom he had not seen since 
Khe Sanh, attended the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	One goal of the new commandant is to lighten the load on Marines  
-- not lessen their training but loosen bureaucratic ropes that can 
make a Marine feel unappreciated, even unwanted. He wants to 
preserve what he calls the ``sheer joy'' of putting on a uniform, 
``knowing you are going to be doing great things that day, with 
great people, for a great cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not having fun then you're missing out on one of the  
intangible benefits that nobody else can duplicate -- not Xerox, not 
Boeing, not IBM.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His mention of U.S. high-tech companies was a sign of concern  
that the allure of higher paychecks in the private sector is making 
it harder to retain Marines and to attract new ones. Jones intends 
to keep more Marines in the ranks by liberating them from what he 
calls ``negative leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some examples:  
</P>
<P>
	--He recalls visiting a barracks in 1995 where newly minted  
Marines of the 2nd Division were received for their first 
assignment. After weeks of basic training and few freedoms, the 
Marines arrived on a Friday evening to discover that on their first 
weekend they would be denied off-base liberty. 
</P>
<P>
	``You start right there with negative leadership,'' Jones told a  
group of Marines in Stuttgart as he recounted the episode. ``You 
don't trust them not to do something stupid. You've got to trust 
them. I'm big on that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--He intends to end announced troop inspections, a practice which  
he said made many Marines feel compelled to spend extra money out 
of their own pockets to buy ``inspection gear'' -- equipment and 
uniform gear kept in pristine condition for display at inspections 
but not otherwise used. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of announcing inspections in advance, commanders will  
perform no-notice inspections that will require Marines to show 
they are reasonably ready for action but not require perfection, 
Jones said. This will cut down on the time Marines spend preparing 
for inspections -- time often stolen from training. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
