<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Li Rebuts Chinese Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The once-elusive leader of a meditation group  
outlawed in China is emerging to defend himself from a Beijing 
propaganda assault, rebutting claims his teachings have driven 
people to suicide and threatened Chinese society. 
</P>
<P>
	Just months ago, requests for interviews with Li Hongzhi were  
declined by his loosely organized network of followers in New York, 
where the spiritual leader moved last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But since the communist government banned his Falun Gong  
movement this week and began detaining hundreds of protesters, Li 
has begun meeting with reporters at a follower's modest Manhattan 
apartment, furnished with a few chairs and a futon sofa. One wall 
is decorated with a collage of snapshots of Li teaching and 
diagrams of the yoga-like movements practiced in Falun Gong. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief interview Friday, Li calmly answered most questions  
with one- or two-sentence answers, showing little or no emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	He passed up opportunities to mend relations with Beijing,  
refusing to say whether he believes in communism and declining to 
urge his followers in China to stop protesting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not ask them to go'' out into the streets, said Li,  
whose pressed blue suit, white shirt and tie made him look more 
like a businessman than a guru. ``I don't have any control over 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Li, 47, grew visibly agitated when asked to rebut recent  
allegations in China's state-run media that his teachings caused 
people to go insane, commit suicide or eschew medicine. One report 
claimed a man slit his stomach looking for his ``wheel of law,'' or 
miniature of the universe mentioned throughout Li's writings. 
</P>
<P>
	In an answer that lasted nearly five minutes, Li said he has  
never encouraged mentally unbalanced or severely ill people to give 
up medication or practice Falun Gong, which is too physically 
demanding for sick people. The spiritual practice involves a blend 
of Buddhism, Taoism, meditation and martial arts. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they die, Falun Gong would be blamed,'' Li said. ``But some  
people still want to practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What is known publicly about Li gives few clues about how a  
junior high school graduate could in just a few years amass such a 
broad following. The group is estimated to have as many as 70 
million members worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Li joined the army at 18, and spent eight years working on a  
horse farm in northeastern China. Later, he was a trumpeter and a 
clerk at a government grain company. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning at a ``young age,'' Li said he studied Falun Gong with  
a spiritual master. ``Other people don't give much attention to 
spiritual cultivation. They go swimming or play ball in their free 
time,'' he said. ``I spent my time practicing spiritual 
cultivation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Falun Gong has been enormously popular, particularly among Li's  
own generation, which grew up in a spiritual void left by the 
radical politics of the Cultural Revolution and the materialistic 
era that has ensued. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice emphasizes morality and improved physical health  
through spiritual teachings and qigong -- martial arts exercises 
practiced by tens of millions of Chinese every day. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its unauthorized status, the sect did not openly clash  
with the Communist Party until April 25. On that day, some 10,000 
believers emerged to surround the Beijing compound where top 
Chinese leaders live in a silent protest against what they said was 
official harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	As protests continued, the government began building a case  
against Li and eventually banned the group on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Li said he worries that the military might violently suppress  
recent protests, as they did 10 years ago during Beijing's 
democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen Square. Busloads of people 
have been taken to detention the past three days in Beijing, where 
crowds have dwindled from hundreds of people to small groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Li said he was puzzled by the crackdown because the group has no  
political ambitions and poses no threat to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the government has treated Falun Gong over  
seriously,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
