<DOCNO> APW19990724.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 20:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Takes Gymastics Gold From US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Silver medals in team gymnastics could  
not have felt more different for the U.S. women and men at the Pan 
American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's competition began with Erinn Dooley pitching forward  
and falling face first to the mat on her balance beam dismount. It 
ended with Jeanette Antolin slipping off the uneven bars. 
</P>
<P>
	There were a lot of bright moments in between for the U.S. women  
Saturday, just not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada claimed the Pan Ams gold before a small but vocal  
pro-Canadian crowd at Winnipeg Arena. The United States, which had 
been favored, was done in by its mistakes and settled for the 
silver. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were not 100 percent prepared,'' U.S. coach Mary Lee Tracy  
said. ``We were doing some new skills, not to mention the world 
championships to think about. But those are excuses. Basically, we 
got beat. They hit more than we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While second was a disappointment for the women, it was a  
satisfying achievement for the U.S. men, a relatively inexperienced 
group that finished behind Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's their world championship team. We haven't selected that  
yet,'' U.S. coach Mark Williams said. ``Some of these guys are 
going to be on that team. This was a great experience to get them 
ready for those trials. I'm very pleased with our performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada won the women's title with 148.944 points. The United  
States had 148.364 and Brazil took the bronze with 147.639. Canada 
also won the Pan Am gold in 1979, the only other year the United 
States failed to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't come in here saying we had to beat the Americans,''  
Canada's Michelle Conway said. ``Our goal was to hit all our events 
and where it placed us, that's where it placed us. We would just 
see what happened. We did that and it paid off for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Yvonne Tousek was the top performer with an all-around  
score of 37.511. Morgan White, at 16 the youngest member of the 
U.S. team, was second at 37.330. 
</P>
<P>
	White and teammates Jennie Thompson (37.230) and Jamie  
Dantzscher (37.061) qualified for the all-around competition Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It definitely didn't turn out the way we wanted,'' Thompson  
said. ``We were coming out here looking to win. But it's a long 
season, we have a long road ahead of us. We want to get ready for 
the world championships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson recovered after falling off the balance beam and posted  
the top U.S. scores in the three other events: floor exercise, 
vault and uneven bars. She earned the highest single-event score of 
the day, a 9.7 with a crowd-pleasing floor exercise done to a 
boogie piano rendition of Chuck Berry's ``Johnny B. Goode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My second pass was new for me, and I was really excited about  
that,'' Thompson said. ``It felt strong. I love doing floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with its early spills, the United States held a slight lead  
over Canada when each had one competitor remaining: Conway on the 
beam and Antolin on the bars. Antolin scored 8.912 after her slip. 
Moments later, Conway hit her landing to a rousing ovation and was 
given a 9.387. 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches and teammates quickly mobbed Conway as the Canadian fans  
stood and cheered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I had to stick it,'' said Conway, who trains in North  
York, Ontario, near Toronto. ``We have a saying in my gym: Own the 
beam, own the meet. If you stick the beam, you're set. I knew I had 
to stick to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came off ... my teammates came over and then I looked  
and saw all those people cheering and thought, `Oh, we won.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba won the men's gold in a runaway, compiling 222.375 points  
and posting the top three individual all-around scores. The United 
States had 216.00 points and Canada 215.15. 
</P>
<P>
	The only disappointment for Williams was that Cuba competed in a  
different round than his team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been nice to have competed at the same time with  
them and see what would have happened,'' Williams said. ``As it 
was, we never even saw the Cubans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Dukta had the top overall score for the Americans at  
53.575. He and teammate Stephen McCain (53.40) both qualified for 
Sunday night's all-around competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal coming out was to hit all my routines and do the best  
job I could for the team,'' Dutka said. ``Getting to the all-around 
really wasn't part of my thinking. I just wanted to hit my sets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba's Eric Lopez had the top all-around score, 56.775. He was  
followed by teammates Adonis Vazquez (54.20) and Lazaro Lamelas 
(54.100). Saturday's scores are not carried over to Sunday's 
competition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
