<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Visits Baseball Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush paid tribute  
Saturday to Hall of Fame inductee Nolan Ryan, who pitched his final 
major league years for a team Bush partly owned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate, appearing at a news  
conference with Ryan before Sunday's induction ceremony, said the 
two share the same values -- ``faith and family and friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are the three most important things in life,'' said  
Bush, who sold his share of the Texas Rangers last year. ``I may 
not be as hard a worker as he is, but I work hard and I understand 
the importance of discipline and focus as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, who has campaigned for Bush in his Texas races, retired in  
1993 after five seasons with the Rangers. He said Bush, part of the 
group that purchased a majority share of the club in 1989, ``paid 
me extremely well'' as a Rangers owner. But, Ryan said, ``now he 
doesn't pay me at all'' for serving as a Bush-appointed member of a 
state commission on parks and wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan was dressed comfortably in a polo shirt, and Bush wore a  
suit and tie on a humid summer day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference in our dress,'' Bush joked, ``is someone who  
doesn't need work and someone who's looking for work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a night in the governor's mansion in Albany, Bush drove  
Saturday to Cooperstown with New York Gov. George Pataki, who has 
been mentioned as a possible running mate if Bush wins the 
Republican nomination for the 2000 election. They were attending a 
Bush campaign fund-raiser in the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush planned to be in the audience during Sunday's induction  
festivities at baseball's shrine, and Pataki was to offer welcoming 
remarks. Bush later was heading for a few days' relaxation at the 
Kennebunkport, Maine, summer home of his parents, former President 
Bush and his wife, Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki said he and Bush ``talked a lot about baseball'' Friday  
night in Albany. But Pataki also said: ``When you get two governors 
together, you always talk a little policy and politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he refused to elaborate. ``This is a weekend about  
baseball,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
