<DOCNO> APW19990724.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 10:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paul Mellon Gifts To Be Exhibited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gifts from the late Paul Mellon, made over  
most of this century, will go on exhibit Nov. 7 at the National 
Gallery of Art, officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The show will include the original wax model of the ``Little  
Dancer Fourteen Years Old'' -- one of 73 items in a trust disclosed 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Mellon died Feb. 1 at 91. His father, Treasury Secretary Andrew  
Mellon, was among the gallery's founders and a major donor in his 
own right. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 paintings, sculptures and prints, contributed by Paul  
Mellon over his lifetime, will appear in the memorial show. The 
list has not been completed, said Patricia O'Connell, a gallery 
spokeswoman, but works will appear by British, French and American 
artists. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in the show from the last gift is ``White Poodle in a  
Punt'' by George Stubbs, a British painter of animals. His pictures 
of horses were favorites of Mellon, who bred a Kentucky Derby 
winner. 
</P>
<P>
	The original dancer has been cast in bronze and reproduced many  
times. One copy went for $11,882,500 at a New York auction three 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only version ... Degas himself every touched or  
saw,'' said Alison Luchs, a sculpture curator at the gallery. 
</P>
<P>
	Degas did the statue about 1880. He adorned it with hair and an  
orange-yellow bodice, which is still there, although the short tutu 
-- the standard ballet dancer's skirt -- has worn out over the years 
and had to be replaced. In earlier centuries many statues wore 
actual clothes, but it was an odd idea in Degas' own time. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Mellon's last gift included 29 wax models by Degas, four in  
bronze and four in plaster. Many of these sculptures -- including 
some of his favorite subjects such as dancers, women bathing and 
horses -- turned up at a foundry after his death in 1917. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit will run through next February, with no admission  
charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:26:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  More Members of China Sect Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's campaign to vanquish an outlawed  
meditation sect intensified Saturday, with police rounding up more 
followers attempting to protest the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Internet, Falun Gong members claimed protesters were  
attempting to converge on Beijing. But there were few signs of any 
activity inside the city as temperatures soared to 105 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	In Beijing's Beihai Park, near the Zhongnanhai compound where  
China's leaders live and work, a group of about 30 Falun Gong 
members was surrounded and detained by police. 
</P>
<P>
	The government banned the group on Thursday after several days  
of silent protests near Zhongnanhai. Since the protests began on 
Tuesday, police have been rounding up Falun Gong adherents 
attempting to protest the crackdown on the group. 
</P>
<P>
	Most would-be demonstrators were forced to board buses and sent  
home, Civil Affairs Ministry officials said. Police recorded the 
names, addresses and employers of those detained and sent them back 
to their homes, reports on the World Wide Web said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exact number of protesters could not be confirmed. However,  
apart from a few scuffles between police and protesters, detentions 
in Beijing and other cities have appeared to involve little 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, dozens of Falun Gong members performed their  
daily meditation Saturday in front of the Chinese Embassy to 
protest the round-up of believers half a world away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stop arresting innocent practitioners,'' and ``We believe in  
truth, compassion, tolerance,'' read signs ringing the protest 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	Later at a press conference, sect members from around North  
America said they feared for the safety and well-being of those 
arrested in China. The Chinese government's description of the 
group as a cult, they said, is a ``misunderstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sect's clash with authorities began on April 25, when 10,000  
believers surrounded the Beijing compound where top Chinese leaders 
live to silently protest what they called official harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has clamped down on all forms of public protest,  
fearing they could catalyze public anger over rising unemployment 
and rampant corruption. Controls have become especially tight as 
China prepares for celebrations Oct. 1 to mark 50 years of 
communist rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Falun Gong, also known as Falun Dafa, draws from Buddhism,  
Taoism, meditation and martial arts. It emphasizes morality and 
improved physical health through spiritual teachings and qigong -- 
martial arts exercises practiced by tens of millions of Chinese 
every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has declared Li Hongzhi, who founded the sect in  
1992 and now lives in New York, an ``evil person,'' describing his 
teachings as a menace to society and his group a would-be political 
organization that dared to challenge Communist Party authority. 
</P>
<P>
	The movement, estimated to have as many as 70 million followers  
inside China, has disavowed any political motives or connections 
with pro-democracy dissident groups. However, human rights groups 
rushed to voice their support. 
</P>
<P>
	``The scope and intensity of the campaign against Falun Gong  
attest to a new high tide of repression in China,'' Xiao Qiang, 
executive director of Human Rights in China said in a statement 
released Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:26:30 </DATE_TIME>
