<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cherokees Elect New Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) -- Members of the nation's second-largest  
Indian tribe voted out a chief on Saturday whose tenure was marred 
by months of turmoil within the tribal government, according to 
unofficial returns. 
</P>
<P>
	Challenger Chad Smith received 7,197 votes, or 56 percent, to  
incumbent Joe Byrd's 5,550 votes, or 44 percent, with all precincts 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd's tenure saw coffers of the 200,000-member Cherokee nation  
slide from a $3.4 million surplus to a projected $18 million 
deficit. Byrd administration officials countered that the chief 
inherited a $1.3 million deficit and has reduced it to less than 
$600,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're humbled, we're honored and we're going to have to take  
into consideration the very solemn charge the Cherokee people have 
put on our shoulders,'' Smith said. ``The turmoil is over. The 
healing begins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd comforted supporters, some in tears.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of a load off my shoulders. I'm not sure President  
Clinton went through as much as I did,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's runoff followed a May primary in which Byrd received  
32 percent of the vote and Smith gained 19 percent, with the 
remainder split among seven other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	About 26,000 of the Cherokees are registered voters. Only about  
half of them voted in the primary. Smith estimated a 20 percent to 
30 percent drop in voter turnout from the primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal member Pamela Bacon said mudslinging by both sides kept  
voters away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's going to settle anything, no matter who  
wins,'' said Bacon, who wouldn't say who she voted for. 
</P>
<P>
	Accusations of misspending have overshadowed much of Byrd's  
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1998 audit by the U.S. Department of Interior found the tribe  
had improperly charged the government $88,000 for legal services 
and transferred $16.1 million in federal money to its operating 
fund without proof the transfers were reimbursements. 
</P>
<P>
	Turmoil started in February 1997 when Byrd fired tribal marshals  
who executed a search warrant for financial documents tied to a 
criminal investigation of his office. His supporters on the tribal 
council later impeached the three tribunal justices, and lawsuits 
and federal probes followed. 
</P>
<P>
	That summer, Smith was arrested as he tried to stop Byrd's  
administration from closing the tribal courthouse, and a crowd 
clashed on the steps a month later when two rival groups of tribal 
marshals fought over its control. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd, 45, ran television ads showing Smith being wrestled to the  
ground by a deputy and urged voters to choose ``responsible 
leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a 48-year-old lawyer, said he would provide the tribe  
with honest leadership, promote culture and improve health care. He 
called upon voters to remove Byrd ``while there's still time to 
save our nation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 17:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray's Approval Wins Carey at 20-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Ray's Approval, a 20-1 shot, nosed out Stay Sound  
to capture the $150,000 Robert F. Carey Memorial Handicap on the 
turf at Hawthorne Racecourse on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray's Approval, ridden by Early Fires, grabbed the early lead  
and stayed in front to the wire, covering the mile in 1:36. 
</P>
<P>
	``This horse doesn't like the dirt,'' said Robert Irwin, trainer  
of Ray's Approval. ``The turf is his home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stay Sound, with Tony D'Amico aboard, finished strongly on the  
outside and was a neck better than favored Inkatha, who was closing 
fast at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I asked him to run, it was a little too late,'' D'Amico  
said. ``We just ran out of real estate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray's Approval paid $41.20, $11.40 and $5, while Stay Sound  
returned $6.40 and $4, and Inkatha was worth $2.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
