<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Fans Want To Watch Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Though Lance Armstrong should win the Tour  
de France on Sunday while most Americans are eating breakfast, his 
adopted hometown will wait to celebrate. 
</P>
<P>
	And while some fans say they will watch the final stage in Paris  
via the Internet, many say they will wait for ABC's national 
telecast of taped coverage in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of cyclists will be out riding Sunday morning. I  
think they'll be able to hold out until Sunday afternoon,'' cyclist 
Jay Aust said. ``Surely some people will be following on the 
Internet. I won't be one of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would be different if a close finish was expected, said Bill  
Reams, a local rider who races with the Violet Crown Sports 
Association. But with Armstrong leading by 7 minutes, 37 seconds 
after winning Saturday's time trial, it would take a catastrophe 
for him to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was a close race you'd probably want to watch it live  
Sunday,'' Reams said. ``If something happens to make it close, 
maybe I will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the 27-year-old Armstrong learned he had testicular  
cancer that spread to his lungs and brain, requiring surgery and 
chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, not only is he on the brink of joining Greg LeMond as the  
only Americans to win the Tour, one of the world's most rugged 
endurance tests, he is about to make believers out of scores who 
doubted he could come back from such a devastating illness. 
</P>
<P>
	A local radio station and downtown brewery will host a party to  
watch the taped footage, and Armstrong's cancer research foundation 
will give away memorabilia, including autographed posters. 
</P>
<P>
	Traci Ripley, director of special events at the Copper Tank  
Brewing Co., said the pub is expecting as many as 500 people to 
attend. Promoters have asked fans to wear yellow, the traditional 
jersey color of the tour leader. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials also are planning a parade and festival when  
Armstrong returns to Austin, but no date has been set. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because it's Lance, we'll be inviting people to come out and  
be in the parade and bring their bikes,'' said Mayor Kirk Watson, 
who, like Armstrong, has survived testicular cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be emotional for a lot of people because he's an  
American winning the Tour de France, one of the greatest races in 
the world. ... And it will be emotional for those who have survived 
cancer. It shows that you can come back to win the best race.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
