<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Sign Claiborne and Gibson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Lions agreed to terms with  
first-round draft choices Chris Claiborne and Aaron Gibson on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Claiborne, a linebacker selected ninth overall out of Southern  
California, will get a $2 million signing bonus in a contract worth 
$7.62 million for four years. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-3, 255-pound Claiborne won the 1998 Butkus Award as  
the nation's top linebacker. He was a first-team All-American last 
season and twice made the All-Pac-10 first team. His totals at USC 
included 312 tackles, 12 sacks, eight interceptions and 23 pass 
deflections. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge Gibson, 6-4 and 380 pounds, was the 27th overall pick  
out of Wisconsin. He got a $3.9 million deal, including a signing 
bonus of $1.675 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A finalist for both the Outland and Lombardi trophies in 1998,  
Gibson, who can play guard or tackle, was a first-team All-American 
and was named to the All-Big Ten first team for a second straight 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The signings were timely because rookies report to the Lions'  
training camp on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always vital to a rookie's development to be in camp on  
time,'' coach Bobby Ross said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
