<HEADLINE> Rogers Recalls Urban Upbringing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Kenny Rogers may represent country, but he says  
he got his street smarts growing up in the city's housing projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a child, this is where the foundation for me and my family  
was laid. It was a wonderful experience to be in a place like 
this,'' the country singer said Friday as he toured the recently 
renovated Allen Parkway Village. ``It's a very real part of my 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers had not walked through the village since moving out in  
1953. 
</P>
<P>
	When Rogers lived in the projects, all the families were white.  
Black and Hispanic families lived in other parts of the city's 
segregated housing projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the separation, he remembers black children coming to  
Allen Parkway to play football. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know the difference. When you're a kid you don't  
stop to analyze black and white,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
