<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires' Man in a Fight of His Own </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- To umpires, he's a hero. To owners and players,  
he's a bully. 
</P>
<P>
	But everyone agrees that Richie Phillips is a brash, boastful  
battler who has been wildly successful on behalf of the umpire's 
union since 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's in the middle of another fight, only this one involves  
Phillips himself and some of the very umpires he's represented for 
more than 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of AL umps say he should be replaced. In March, 14 voted  
against giving Phillips a new five-year contract, saying they 
wanted a less confrontational lawyer such as Ron Shapiro of 
Baltimore, who represents Cal Ripken and Kirby Puckett. 
</P>
<P>
	``They do not like me personally, do not like my style,''  
Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	On that, the opposition group agrees. They think he's misjudged  
umpires' leverage with baseball and even their own unity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am adamantly opposed to this kind of leadership,'' said AL  
umpire Dave Phillips, a 29-year veteran who is no relation. ``There 
are times when you pull out your gun, your mortar and go 
winner-take-all. But communication and negotiation are the most 
important ingredients we need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips says he doesn't care that some umpires are against him.  
He says he's fighting for the hard core, the group intent on 
resigning Sept. 2 because baseball refuses to negotiate a new labor 
contract before the current deal expires on Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	He is not your classic, buttoned-down Philadelphia lawyer.  
</P>
<P>
	When the 280-pound, 6-foot-2 Phillips doesn't get what he wants,  
he screams, he throws things, he files unfair labor practice 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The perfect image of his negotiating style was evident eight  
years ago. He didn't like what he was hearing from baseball 
management lawyer Robert Kheel during a bargaining session, so he 
hurled an office chair through the wall of a conference room at 
Willkie Farr &AMP; Gallagher, one of the nation's most prestigious law 
firms. 
</P>
<P>
	When the sides reached an agreement and held a news conference  
later that day, Phillips was proud of his destruction, pointing it 
out as if it were some sort of battle scar. 
</P>
<P>
	Kheel never sent him a bill, Phillips said.  
</P>
<P>
	``He provoked it,'' Phillips recalled Friday, laughing. ``He  
knew he deserved that hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the only time Phillips made baseball owners pay.  
</P>
<P>
	When he became the lawyer for the Major League Umpires  
Association in 1978, rookie umpires made $17,500 and the most 
senior veterans got $40,000. In the labor contract that expires 
Dec. 31, they make a minimum of $95,000 and can earn up to 
$282,500, including the postseason bonuses they all receive. 
</P>
<P>
	The 58-year-old burly Phillips scares owners and management  
officials even more than players' association head Donald Fehr and 
his chief lawyer, Gene Orza. 
</P>
<P>
	Kheel, citing the delicate situation, wouldn't say a word about  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why not?'' Phillips wanted to know.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked to assess his strengths and weaknesses, Phillips said the  
people who sit across bargaining tables from him should do that. 
Told they wouldn't, he paused, reflected and said: ``I don't have 
any weak points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips graduated from with an economics degree from Villanova,  
where he played guard and linebacker on the Wildcats' team that 
beat Wichita State in the 1961 Sun Bowl. He spent 1962 as an 
assistant football coach there and coached the freshman team the 
following year. 
</P>
<P>
	After graduating from Villanova Law School, he became a defense  
lawyer from 1967-69 and spent three years as an assistant district 
attorney in Philadelphia under Arlen Specter, now a U.S. Senator. 
</P>
<P>
	After that came the private sector. He was a lawyer for the  
Philadelphia Transport Worker's Union from 1972-73, the 
Philadelphia Carpenters' Union from 1972-74 and the Philadelphia 
76ers from 1974-76. Then he switched sides and became the 
negotiator for the NBA referees' union from 1976-83. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, he was the agent for catcher Mike Scioscia, and he  
occasionally represented pitching great Steve Carlton. In 1978, he 
was approached to represent the umpires by Jerry Crawford, now the 
union president, Bruce Froemming and Paul Runge, now the NL's 
executive director of umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a year, Phillips led umpires in their first-ever strike.  
When they ended the walkout after seven weeks, they had their first 
collective bargaining agreement, average raises of $7,000 and, for 
the first time in baseball history, two weeks' vacation during the 
regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	He still considers that his greatest success.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had to break the mind-set of baseball in dealing with the  
umpires,'' he said. ``The umpires were advised repeatedly by letter 
and telegrams that they had been permanently replaced and would 
never work again in baseball. Despite those threats and edicts, 
they hung together and they hung in for a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next fight came in 1984, when umpires struck the first four  
games of the postseason. They threatened another strike in 1985, 
struck for over a day in 1991 and missed most season openers. Then 
they were locked out for the first eight days of the 1995 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, it's been one battle after another:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Umpires tried to strike the 1996 postseason, angered when  
Roberto Alomar received only a five-day suspension for spitting at 
John Hirschbeck -- a penalty that was delayed until the following 
regular season. Phillips forced owners to get a federal injunction 
to prevent a walkout. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He was incensed when players won an arbitration ruling that  
forced owners to pay them for all suspensions for on-field conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Umpires threatened to eject players for even the slightest  
argument. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Until an arbitrator ordered him to, he wouldn't allow umpires  
carry stopwatches to make sure innings didn't start before 
television commercials ended. 
</P>
<P>
	-- He filed a grievance over an attempt to get umpires to call  
the strike zone as it's defined in the rule book, and another to 
prevent umpires from working the Baltimore Orioles' exhibition 
series against Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	When players held a survey to rate umpires, he ridiculed it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're patently absurd. I've even been told that some  
players had their kids fill them out,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the umpires got him the most publicity, he spent most of  
his time on other work. He was lawyer for the Horsemens' Benevolent 
and Protective Association from 1984-91 and has been the lawyer for 
the Professional Association of Golf Officials since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	His main job is chairman, president and chief executive officer  
of Pilot Air Freight Inc., which he says has 1,500 employees in 56 
offices and generates close to $200 million annually in revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	A former Pilot employee, Gepke Wils, sued him for sexual  
harassment, claiming in federal court papers last November that he 
pressed her for sexual favors from 1995-1997. Wils also filed 
complaints in October 1997 with the Equal Employment Opportunity 
Commission and the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is absolutely no factual basis to any of these  
allegations,'' Phillips said last autumn. He said both agencies 
investigated but found no merit to her complaint. Officials at the 
agencies said they don't release information on such complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips and his wife Ellenanne have been married 35 years and  
have four children - two daughters and two sons, ranging in age 
from 28 to 34. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 20:31:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Unveiling New Air Quality Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Revamping a 2-decade-old system, the  
Environmental Protection Agency is issuing a new air quality index 
that gives more detailed health warnings on the harms of air 
pollution and ways people can protect themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore was announcing the new index today at a  
groundbreaking for a children's hospital in New York City. He said 
a category added to the chart would particularly benefit children 
with asthma and others with special respiratory conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new air quality index is a critical tool Americans need to  
protect their health,'' Gore said in prepared remarks. ``It will 
empower parents and communities to protect children, particularly 
the 6 million children who suffer from asthma.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The air quality index is used by local weather forecasters and  
others to gauge the health effects of air pollution on a given day. 
Pollution measurements are divided into ranges and a health 
advisory is given based on the day's ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the current standards have not been updated since their  
introduction in 1976 and are not always used consistently, 
according to the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised model is aimed at providing a uniform nationwide  
format that weather forecasters can use to relay information about 
when air pollution poses a health risk and what precautions people 
can take. The index looks at five major air pollutants: smog, soot, 
sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide and nitrogen dioxide. 
</P>
<P>
	A change in the levels of any or all of these pollutants can  
shift the health protection warning for that day. For example, if 
the index indicates moderate air quality, people who are unusually 
sensitive to pollution are advised to limit their outdoor activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The updated chart adds a new warning for when air quality might  
be unhealthy for sensitive groups, such as children and adults with 
respiratory problems, including asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also was using the event to urge Congress to pass the  
administration's $68 million plan to attack childhood asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the money -- $50 million -- would be used for competitive  
state grants to identify and treat poor children served by Medicaid 
who have asthma. The initiative would help schools educate children 
and parents on how to avoid attacks, support research into 
environmental hazards and pay for a public information campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Lose Brock for 6-8 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco Giants' trade for Livan  
Hernandez was perfect timing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after acquiring Hernandez in a trade Saturday with  
Florida, the Giants learned right-hander Chris Brock will be 
sidelined six to eight weeks with a torn anterior cruciate ligament 
in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Brock was hurt in the second inning of a 6-5 win over Cincinnati  
on Friday night, when he tripped over first base and fell hard on 
the knee while legging out an infield single. 
</P>
<P>
	Brock stayed in the game and pitched four more innings. He left  
after six innings with a no-decision. However, the knee was still 
sore after the game and the Giants had him undergo an MRI Saturday 
that revealed the tear. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez, 24, who helped the Marlins to the 1997 World Series  
title and became just the second rookie to win Series MVP honors, 
will take Brock's place in San Francisco's rotation. He'll make his 
first start for the Giants on Wednesday against St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Brock, who emerged from a spring training competition to win the  
job as the Giants' fifth starter, was 6-8 with a 5.48 ERA in 19 
starts. He had 76 strikeouts and 41 walks in 106 2-3 innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
