<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 16:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kennedy Plane Wreckage Transported  
</P>
<P>
	OTIS AIR FORCE BASE, Mass. (AP) -- Two flatbed trucks under  
police escort transported wreckage from the John F. Kennedy Jr. 
plane crash to the Coast Guard hangar where it will be examined in 
detail. Federal investigators hope to learn what happened July 16 
that caused the plane to dive into the sea off the coast of 
Martha's Vineyard killing Kennedy, his wife Carolyn Bessette 
Kennedy and her sister Lauren Bessette. Tonight, a private memorial 
service will be held for the Bessette sisters in Connecticut. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-Milosevic Protests Compete  
</P>
<P>
	NIS, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Competing anti-government groups held  
rallies in Serbian cities today, drawing thousands of people but 
failing to unite against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
About 25,000 protesters, the largest opposition gathering in the 
last month of rallies, turned up in the southern city of Nis at a 
demonstration called by Vuk Draskovic, of the Serbian Renewal 
movement. In Sombor, near the northern border with Hungary, 5,000 
people rallied, calling for Milosevic to resign. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Massacre Hurts NATO Efforts  
</P>
<P>
	GRACKO, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The massacre of 14 Serbs threatened to  
set back efforts to end Kosovo's cycle of violence, and NATO 
officials acknowledged today that such acts of vengeance are beyond 
their control. It was the worst since NATO peacekeepers entered 
Kosovo six weeks ago. Villagers blamed ethnic Albanians for the 
attack. Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic blamed the massacre 
on NATO and the United Nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Attacks GOP Tax Plan  
</P>
<P>
	ASPEN, Colo. (AP) -- President Clinton, mingling with big-money  
Democratic donors, described the Republicans' tax-cutting plan in 
doomsday terms today, saying it would ``imperil the future 
stability of the country.'' ``It doesn't make sense,'' Clinton said 
in his weekly radio address, asserting that the GOP program would 
soak up money needed to fix Social Security, Medicare and other 
social programs. In reply, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, 
R-Texas, praised the $792 billion tax cut passed last week as 
returning surplus federal money to the people to keep it from being 
spent in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Confident on Morocco  
</P>
<P>
	ASPEN, Colo. (AP) -- President Clinton expressed confidence today  
that Morocco will remain a close friend and partner in Middle East 
peacemaking under its new king, Mohamed VI. Clinton and his wife, 
Hillary, were returning to Washington from an abbreviated 
fund-raising weekend in Colorado, then were flying to Morocco for 
the funeral of King Hassan II, who died yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Plane Crash in Fiji Kills 17  
</P>
<P>
	SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- A plane crashed into a mountain in a remote  
area of the Pacific tourist island of Fiji today, killing all 17 
people on board. The Brazilian-built Air Fiji Bandeirante went down 
in rugged jungle near Nasevou village on Fiji's main island of Viti 
Levu, about 40 miles northwest of the capital, Suva. 

</P>
<P>
	More Members of China Sect Detained  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's campaign to vanquish an outlawed  
meditation sect intensified today, with police rounding up more 
followers attempting to protest the ban. On the Internet, Falun 
Gong members claimed protesters were attempting to converge on 
Beijing. But there were few signs of any activity inside the city 
as temperatures soared to 105 degrees. In Beijing's Beihai Park, 
about 30 Falun Gong members were surrounded and detained by police. 

</P>
<P>
	Missing U.S. Army Plane Sought  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A massive aerial search for a missing  
U.S. Army spy plane today focused on an area of winding brown 
rivers and hot, dense jungles near Colombia's southwestern border 
where leftist rebels are strong. Airplanes and helicopters from the 
U.S. military, State Department and Customs Service as well as from 
the Colombian military helped search for the plane, which took off 
from a Colombian military base yesterday morning on a ``routine 
counter-drug mission,'' the U.S. Army said. There was no ground 
search so far. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Warned of Lax Plane Security  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The man who commandeered an All Nippon Airways  
jumbo jet and fatally stabbed its pilot wrote a letter to the 
Transport Ministry saying Japanese airlines were easy prey for 
hijackers, an official said today. Yuji Nishizawa managed to get 
the knife on board by taking it out of a bag he had checked earlier 
in the day, when he flew from Osaka to Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets 2, Cubs 1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rookie Octavio Dotel struck out nine in 7 1-3  
strong innings and Robin Ventura's tiebreaking homer gave the New 
York Mets a 2-1 victory over the Chicago Cubs today. Edgardo 
Alfonzo went 3-for-4 and homered for the Mets, who have won four 
straight. Dotel (3-1) gave up only Sammy Sosa's major 
league-leading 36th home run in the third inning. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
