<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Pres. Denies Oil Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's president, in a letter to  
President Clinton, denied charges his country was flooding the U.S. 
market with cheap oil. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has never been, nor is, Venezuela's strategy,'' President  
Hugo Chavez said in the letter, obtained by The Associated Press on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	A coalition of small U.S. oil companies based in Oklahoma filed  
a ``dumping'' complaint last month with the Commerce Department, 
accusing Venezuela, Iraq, Mexico and Saudi Arabia of selling 
petroleum on the U.S. market at prices below costs of production. 
</P>
<P>
	``This action is totally contrary to the free market and to the  
close energy relationship that has benefited our countries,'' 
Chavez said in the letter, sent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Commerce Department finds in favor of the U.S. companies,  
it could impose tariffs on the imported oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela competes with Saudi Arabia and Mexico as the No. 1  
exporter of oil to the United States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
