<HEADLINE> Flynt To Fight Complaint Vs. Store </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Larry Flynt doesn't intend to move his adult  
bookstore out of a downtown building without a fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hustler magazine publisher is planning to fight a complaint  
filed by the city against his store. The complaint was filed 
Thursday after Flynt refused an eviction notice to vacate the 
building. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt's attorney, H. Louis Sirkin, said city officials are  
trying to force his client out because they do not approve of the 
Hustler Books, Magazines &AMP; Gifts store. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an attempt to silence and censor,'' Sirkin said. ``We're  
going to fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant City Solicitor Geri Hernandez Geiler said the store is  
occupying the building illegally. She said the city now owns the 
building and it must make room for an arts center. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not trying to run any of those businesses in that area  
out of town,'' Ms. Geiler said. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing is set for Aug. 13 in Municipal Court.  
  	   	
</P>
