<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Dept. Says Terror Has Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Today's terrorists find ways to raise their  
own money -- through drug trafficking, for example -- rather than 
rely on direct help from foreign governments, the State 
Department's acting counterterrorism coordinator said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The character of international terrorism has shifted somewhat  
since 1980, when Americans were being held hostage in the U.S. 
Embassy in Iran, Michael Sheehan told the Senate Foreign Relations 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Groups involved in the bombing nearly a year ago of U.S.  
embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, he said, 
``are more in the mold of the new terrorist threat -- groups that 
are often self-financed with less direct linkage to state 
sponsors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fears for the safety of diplomats and other Americans abroad  
have grown with the approach of the Aug. 7 anniversary of the 
bombings, which killed 224 people including 12 Americans and 
injured thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	A growing connection of narcotics trafficking and terrorism can  
be seen around the globe, Sheehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can see it in Colombia, all the way through the Bekaa  
Valley in the Middle East, all the way out to South Asia and in 
Afghanistan and in other parts of the world,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheehan spoke at his confirmation hearing Friday. He is the  
Clinton administration's nominee to hold the job permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's terrorists also are more violent. ``These terrorists  
want a `body count,''' Sheehan said. ``For this reason, our efforts 
against terrorism must remain strong and consistent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because domestic U.S. anti-terrorism measures are strong, he  
said, terrorist groups still prefer to attack targets outside the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheehan promised that if he is confirmed, his top priority will  
be to bring to justice the bombers responsible for the attack 
against the embassies in East Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the State Department said the U.S. Embassy in Chad  
reopened Friday, a day after it was closed because of a telephoned 
bomb threat. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-hour search of the building uncovered nothing, spokesman  
James P. Rubin said. He said embassy management decided to suspend 
operations for the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. Embassy in Mozambique remained closed for a  
fifth day Friday because of security concerns. The State Department 
has declined to discuss specific reasons for the shutdown. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
