<DOCNO> APW19990724.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 23:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona's Dellucci Having Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Arizona Diamondbacks outfielder David Dellucci  
said Saturday night that he likely will undergo season-ending 
surgery on his injured left wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Dellucci said tests have shown the bone in his wrist is damaged  
and he has been told it may be a risk to his career if he continues 
to play. The team has given him a couple of days to decide if he 
wants to rest awhile and try to play, tough it out now or have the 
surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dellucci seemed to be reluctantly realizing that surgery was  
the only logical course. 
</P>
<P>
	``First, I have to accept it, and that may take a couple of  
days,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dellucci, one of the team's most popular players, started eight  
of the last 10 games before sitting out the last two. He was 
hitting .516 in those eight starts (16-for-31). For the season, 
Dellucci is batting .394 in 109 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would love to tell you that ice and rest would fix it up,  
but unfortunately I don't think this is one of those deals,'' 
Dellucci said. ``I can tough it out, but that may be jeopardizing 
my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the wrist bothered him the last two years and worsened  
over the past couple of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It started getting unbearable last week, bad enough for me to  
complain about it, and I don't complain about much,'' Dellucci 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it hurts constantly.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't even wash my hair with my left hand,'' Dellucci said.  
``The thing that got me worried was it got worse over the All-Star 
break without me doing anything.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
