<HEADLINE> Elizabeth Dole Campaigns in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKENY, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole sharpened her focus on next  
month's GOP straw poll Saturday, suggesting some campaigns might 
not survive a poor showing in the media-driven event. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you have made it significant,'' Dole said, meeting  
with reporters after opening her latest campaign trip in Iowa. 
``The press, the media truly have made it significant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Republican Party has scheduled the straw poll Aug. 14  
to raise money, but the event has taken on a life of its own and is 
getting huge attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates have responded by stepping up their campaign efforts  
in the state, hoping to avoid an embarrassing showing that could 
dampen fund raising as the opening of the primary season nears. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole was asked if a strong showing was needed to allow some  
candidates to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe for some. I don't think it is in our campaign,'' Mrs.  
Dole said. ``I don't think it would be do or die. Obviously, we 
want to do well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole opened an intense-three day trip with a town  
hall-style meeting in Ankeny, where 300 backers showed up to hear 
the stump speech and ask a few questions. 
</P>
<P>
	She was crisscrossing the state repeating that effort, and  
conceded that the emergence of the straw poll have jangled some 
campaign schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, in terms of our time, I'd say we're spending more  
time in Iowa than other places,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``I think right 
now, we're spending more time here than in maybe some of the other 
early states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the candidates are spending very heavily and putting a  
premium on a strong showing. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander 
sent out a fund-raising letter seeking to collect $1 million for 
his straw poll effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to Texas Gov. George W. Bush have said they'll bring 5,000  
people to the event, and publisher Steve Forbes is spending 
heavily. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole said her focus is on the grassroots basics.  
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, it's doing what's important in Iowa and New  
Hampshire, which is retail campaigning,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``If that 
is in any way bypassed, it will be pretty serious in terms of the 
future of the caucuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's precinct caucuses, which open the presidential nominating  
season, are followed closely by the nation's first primary in New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole rejected suggestions the straw poll was adding new  
early pressure to the candidates, noting she was campaigning for 
her husband during the last campaign when the GOP ran a similar 
straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the same in '96,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``That's one of the  
advantages of having had some experience. To me it's not 
frustrating, because you've got to build toward the caucuses and 
this is part of the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's basically what we were doing long before the straw poll  
kicked in and will be doing long after,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
