<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Faces Argentina in Key Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- There will be no chance of an  
Olympic gold medal in Australia unless the United States wins today 
against Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men's basketball team plays its most important  
non-Olympic game in seven years, needing a victory to qualify for 
the 2000 Games in Sydney. Not since 1992, the year of the original 
Dream Team, has the United States been forced to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our next game is the most important game that our team could  
ever have to play, to have to qualify with the way this is set 
up,'' coach Larry Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other semifinal, it's Puerto Rico vs. Canada.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite winning the gold medal at the 1996 Olympics, the United  
States has to qualify for the 2000 Games because of its finish in 
the 1998 World Championships. NBA players did not play there 
because of the league's lockout. Yugoslavia won, and the United 
States finished third with CBA players. 
</P>
<P>
	In this tournament, the United States had no problem with  
Argentina in the first round, winning by 31. 
</P>
<P>
	In eight games overall, the U.S. team won by an average of 32.6  
points and allowed no opponent to score more than 76. The only team 
that kept things tight into the second half was Brazil, which 
pulled within three points before the Americans pulled away. 
</P>
<P>
	If there was one memorable moment for the Argentineans in the  
first round, it came when 19-year-old Andres Nocioni threw down a 
dunk over Kevin Garnett and Tim Duncan. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's between Kevin Garnett and that man,'' Tim Hardaway  
said, drawing a laugh from Garnett. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still wish that kid the best,'' Garnett said Thursday. ``I  
hope he makes the league off that and gets a whole bunch of 
endorsements, to tell you the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canada-Puerto Rico game will be a rematch of what might have  
been the best game in the first two rounds -- Wednesday night's 
five-point victory by Puerto Rico in a game the host team needed to 
win by at least four points to avoid the Americans in the 
semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Steve Nash made a turnover late in that game,  
preventing Canada from getting off a decent attempt on its final 
shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be hard for them to beat us twice,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico is shooting for its second consecutive Olympic  
berth. Using many of the same players who are still on the team, 
Puerto Rico finished 10th -- ahead of only Angola and South Korea -- 
in the 12-team 1996 Olympic field. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans took the day off Friday, their first rest after  
playing eight games in eight nights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans are staying in Rio Mar -- almost an hour outside  
San Juan -- and must make a long bus ride before and after every 
game. In addition, they played three consecutive games that started 
at 10 p.m. EDT during the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday night's 115-76 victory over Puerto Rico was a lift,  
coming before a raucous pro-Puerto Rican crowd of more than 12,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait until Saturday gets here so we can go out and do  
what we have to do,'' Gary Payton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Hardaway: ``We're on a mission -- to go to Australia and  
play in the Olympics. We don't want to give anybody any ideas. We 
want to go out there and play with our minds and our bodies and 
show everybody that we are the best team in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The semifinal winners meet in the gold medal game Sunday at 8  
p.m. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
