<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux-Penguins Deal Pushed Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Former Pittsburgh Penguins superstar Mario  
Lemieux has pushed back to next week his goal of closing a deal to 
buy the financially troubled team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux had been optimistic about wrapping up things by Friday,  
but putting all the documents together was taking longer than 
expected, his attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The closing will likely happen sometime next week, attorney Doug  
Campbell told the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette on Thursday, citing the 
volume of work required to finalize the $50 million deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell did not return calls for comment on Friday, but U.S.  
Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz's office confirmed that the deal 
was still pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Markovitz agreed to give Lemieux until Monday to  
secure funding from investors. Lemieux then has until Aug. 5 to 
complete the rest of the transaction, which includes signing a new 
lease with SMG and a new television contract with Fox Sports Net 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, details of a new lease showed the Penguins paying SMG  
$1.8 million a year until 2007 in order to play at the Civic Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Leeper, executive director of the Public Auditorium  
Authority, said the Penguins would really only pay about $1 million 
a year in rent, because SMG has agreed to pick up game-day expenses 
for the entire regular season -- which should end up costing about 
$800,000. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a fraction of the $6 million to $7 million annually the  
club has shelled out in previous years, a burden many have blamed 
for the team's current predicament. 
</P>
<P>
	However, attorneys continue to negotiate terms of the contract.  
After listening to details of Lemieux's deal with SMG, Markovitz 
issued a memorandum stating that he did not approve a settlement 
between the two groups. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG attorney Daniel Shapira did not return phone calls Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Part of the pressure to close the deal comes from the NHL. The  
Penguins must start selling tickets and signing player contracts 
for the coming season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
