<DOCNO> APW19990724.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 04:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *John Doohan    	
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- John Doohan, chief librarian for The  
Kansas City Star and The Kansas City Times for almost three 
decades, died Wednesday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Doohan ran the newspapers' third-floor clip library, where  
generations of journalists went to find the correct date, address 
or circumstance of Kansas City history. The Times was later folded 
into The Star and is no longer published. 
</P>
<P>
	Doohan, who retired in 1978, also worked as a reporter, copy  
reader, feature writer and grain reporter before becoming head 
librarian in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1966 to 1977, he wrote the ``Forty Years Ago'' column,  
which summarized news events from the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Mary Catherine Doohan; two  
daughters, Monica Flynn and Juliana Fiser; four grandchildren and 
one great-grandchild. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Paul E. Flato    	
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Paul E. Flato, a retired jeweler whose  
clients included movie producers and stars, died July 17. He was 
98. 
</P>
<P>
	Flato opened his own jewelry shop in the early 1920s, becoming  
one of the foremost designers of his era. He opened a branch in 
Beverly Hills, Calif., and designed jewelry for several films. 
</P>
<P>
	Flato moved to Mexico City later in life and established a shop  
there before returning to Texas in 1990. 

</P>
<P>
                           *King Hassan II    	
</P>
<P>
	RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- King Hassan II, who ignored regional  
taboos to help forge Mideast peace and ruled his North African 
country for 38 years, died Friday of a heart attack. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Hassan played a precarious balancing act in the Middle East,  
bringing Arabs and Israelis closer together, partly because tens of 
thousands of Israelis are of Moroccan origin. In the 1970s, he made 
several secret diplomatic overtures to Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	He helped bring about the 1979 peace treaty between Israel and  
Egypt, as well as subsequent agreements between Israel and both the 
Palestine Liberation Organization and Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first major initiative as king, he met Algeria's  
then-president, Ahmed Ben Bella, in Bamako, the capital of 
neighboring Mali, and made sweeping concessions that led to 12 
years of peace in the Sahara. 
</P>
<P>
	Hassan tried to improve the country's human rights record. He  
became a pioneer in the Arab world by ordering the release of 
dozens of political prisoners in recent years, and by ordering 
compensation for the families of prisoners who disappeared or were 
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	In May 1995, Hassan mediated peace talks between Israeli Foreign  
Minister Shimon Peres and PLO chief Yasser Arafat. A summit of the 
world's Muslim leaders hosted by the king in 1994 resulted in a 
public statement against Islamic extremism. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, he oversaw the establishment of an elected lower house  
of parliament, in which leftists gained a majority in elections. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Frank M. Johnson Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Frank M. Johnson Jr., a federal judge  
who issued key rulings that helped bring down racial barriers 
across the South and improved the treatment of prisoners and mental 
patients, died Friday of pneumonia. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	His rulings, beginning with a pivotal 1956 decision that marked  
a victory for the Montgomery bus boycott, outlawed segregation 
across a wide spectrum -- on public transportation and in parks, 
restaurants, libraries and schools. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, he signed the original order to integrate the  
University of Alabama, and he participated in the decision that 
ultimately became the ``one man, one vote'' principle established 
by the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the most dramatic orders of his career, Johnson  
cleared the way for Martin Luther King Jr. and swelling ranks of 
voting rights marchers to make their historic 1965 march from Selma 
to Montgomery despite Wallace's attempt to block it. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite accolades from civil rights groups, Johnson insisted  
throughout his career that he was simply following the law and was 
hardly a liberal. He also showed firm resolve despite the violence 
of the times. A cross was once burned on his lawn, and his mother's 
house was bombed. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was nominated to be FBI director by President Carter in  
1977 but eventually withdrew because of health problems. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was appointed by President Eisenhower to the district  
court in Montgomery in 1955, Johnson was 37 and the youngest 
federal judge in the country. Barely a year later, he joined in the 
2-1 ruling that outlawed segregation of public transportation, 
giving King and the bus boycott in Montgomery a victory that helped 
jump-start the civil rights movement. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Tom McPhail    	
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Tom McPhail, former head and co-founder  
of Ireland International news agency, died Friday of cancer. He was 
47. 
</P>
<P>
	McPhail started his career in 1969 as a reporter on the Drogheda  
Independent. He went on to work as a news editor for both the Irish 
Press newspaper group and for Britain's Granada Television. 
</P>
<P>
	McPhail and three colleagues founded Ireland International in  
1982 to cover Ireland for British and foreign media. He retired in 
April 1998 because of illness. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Adelaide, his parents, four brothers  
and two sisters. 

</P>
<P>
                           *David N. Myers    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- David N. Myers, a philanthropist whose college  
alma mater was renamed in his honor, died Thursday. He was 99. 
</P>
<P>
	He helped keep the books for his father's barrel-making business  
until going to work for an asphalt business where he became 
president in 1931. He later bought the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers graduated in 1922 from Dyke College in Cleveland and  
became a major benefactor. He donated $2 million for renovation of 
its downtown office tower. The school was renamed David N. Myers 
College in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Herbert Roth    	
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Herbert Roth, an Army sergeant who  
recovered a small church bell in the war ruins of Anzio, Italy, in 
1944 and sent it home in May to mark the village's liberation, died 
Thursday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	The bell, which was used for calling people into Mass at Saints  
Pio and Antonio Church, is 9 inches tall and 5 inches wide. On its 
side is the protruding figure of a lion's head, a papal symbol 
marking the church's founding in 1856. 
</P>
<P>
	After keeping the bell on a shelf at home for a half-century,  
Roth donated it in 1997 to the Italian American Community Center in 
suburban Rochester. 
</P>
<P>
	With Roth's blessing, a delegation from Rochester returned the  
bell to Anzio on Memorial Day to commemorate the 55th anniversary 
of the village's liberation. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Emma Tenayuca    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Emma Tenayuca, a labor organizer who led  
pecan shellers in a 1938 strike, died Friday. She was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tenayuca was among Communist Party members targeted by  
rioters during a 1939 disturbance in her hometown of San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	She moved to California in 1948 but returned to Texas in the  
1960s and taught school there. She retired in 1982. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Kevin Wilkinson    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Kevin Wilkinson, a rock drummer who played with  
such groups as Squeeze and China Crisis, apparently committed 
suicide on July 17. He was 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkinson played last summer with singer Howard Jones in a  
popular 1980s revival tour in the United States that also included 
Culture Club and Human League. He also recently toured America with 
the Proclaimers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, he called on friends in the music business to join  
him in the successful KosovAid concert in his hometown of Swindon, 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1970s, Wilkinson was part of the ``art punk'' band  
Stadium Dogs. Later, he joined China Crisis, appearing on four of 
the band's albums. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, he joined the re-formed '70s band Squeeze, playing on  
the album ``Ridiculous.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Anne Woolliams    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Anne Woolliams, a British ballet director who was  
instrumental in establishing the international reputation of 
Germany's Stuttgart Ballet, died July 8 of cancer. She was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout her career she was well-regarded for both her  
teaching and direction. She also danced in several films and 
musicals, including the 1948 film ``Red Shoes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With John Cranko, director of West Germany's Stuttgart Ballet,  
she helped to develop Stuttgart as a major international success 
and to transform the part-time student classes into the country's 
leading ballet school, now called the John Cranko School. 
</P>
<P>
	She was artistic director of the Australian Ballet from 1976 to  
1978, and then first Dean of Dance at Australia's Victorian College 
of the Arts in Melbourne until 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Her book on teaching, ``Ballettsaal,'' was published in Germany  
in 1973 and in English as ``Ballet Studio'' in 1978. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
