<DOCNO> APW19990724.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 10:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Work More Outside of Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Born in 1909, Maurice Rovner lived over his  
hardware store, selling the nails that patched northwest 
Baltimore's row houses. Even on his one day off customers came 
knocking -- because they knew where to find him. Would he sell them 
some mousetraps, three for a dime? 
</P>
<P>
	Born in 1960, his grandson Dave Rovner rides the computer  
revolution, opening a laptop easily on his kitchen table, taking a 
cell phone call while out with his kids, checking e-mail while on 
vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	During this hard-working century, when productivity grew an  
average 2 percent a year, Americans increasingly toiled outside the 
home: on factory assembly lines, steelyards, in office cubicles. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the century's start and finish, workers such as the  
Rovners earned their keep from home, steps from their families, 
blurring the line between home and work and sometimes paying a 
price for doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	Work hovered over every minute of Maurice Rovner's day.  
Nowadays, his grandson totes it almost everywhere. Millions of 
workers fret whether to answer right away when the boss e-mails on 
a Saturday. Tele-work is clean and cutting-edge, but the technology 
that frees us to bring the office home shackles us, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Little by little, lines are being drawn. ``People are creating  
more boundaries, not without difficulty,'' says Ellen Galinsky, 
president of the Families and Work Institute. ``You have to invent 
it yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	In colonial times, work and home were one. Mostly farmers or  
craftsmen, men and women worked as full partners in supporting the 
family and raising children. Married women were called yoke-mates. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the 1830s, ``boss'' had become a commonly used word. In  
1800, just 12 percent of people had one, but that figure was 40 
percent by 1860. 
</P>
<P>
	As this century opened, a majority of people depended on wage  
labor for the first time. By the end of World War I, as industry 
churned out goods propelled by a new gospel of efficiency, 87 
percent of wage earners worked for corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, homes were still workplaces.  
</P>
<P>
	A close look at one apartment building in New York reveals a  
hive of at-home enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	In one apartment of what is now the Lower East Side Tenement  
Museum, Nathalie Gumpertz, a single mother, worked as a seamstress. 
In other dim, dusty apartments, tenants made brooms and cigars. It 
was 1900, and 25,000 New Yorkers took in ``home work,'' finishing 
the manual work started elsewhere. It was an essential way to 
supplement family income. 
</P>
<P>
	At best, working conditions at home were primitive. But as more  
and more family members took jobs outside the home, they 
encountered horrific workplaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Holzman began working in a rudimentary New York furniture  
factory in 1921 at the age of 14, a year after leaving his native 
Warsaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dust was so thick, you had to not only wear a handkerchief  
over your mouth to breathe, you couldn't see someone standing three 
feet away,'' he told oral history researchers from New York 
University's Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives. 
</P>
<P>
	Children's wages were crucial, since family income was often  
seasonal and injuries were common. Handing the weekly pay packet 
over to your parents was a ritual of childhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up until the day I was married, I handed it in,'' says Cecelia  
Ohlandt, a gregarious 81-year-old who had to leave school at age 
16. ``My mother and father both worked, and still, if you wanted to 
have a fairly decent life -- at least have some clothes -- this is 
the way it had to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It took bloody strikes, lethal accidents and muckraking  
journalism to galvanize reform. In 1906, Upton Sinclair's landmark 
book, ``The Jungle,'' exposed the abuses of the meatpacking 
industry. In 1911, some 146 women died in a fire in New York's 
Triangle Shirtwaist factory, some because doors had been locked to 
keep them on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	A patchwork of worker protections was born, first aimed at women  
and children. States enacted workers' compensation, restrictions on 
child labor and an eight-hour day in some industries. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until the late 1930s, however, that reforms became  
national and applicable to all. And even today, immigrants in New 
York or Los Angeles -- like workers in many other countries around 
the globe -- toil in filthy, dangerous sweatshops that earlier 
reformers sought to eradicate. 
</P>
<P>
	In these turbulent decades, home truly became ``... Sweet Home''  
-- a consciously separate oasis in a cruel and hurried world. 
</P>
<P>
	Women ideally stayed home, although in reality growing numbers  
went to work before marriage. Homes evolved from work and social 
centers bustling with business partners, boarders and neighbors, to 
private family fiefdoms, notes historian Tamara Hareven. 
</P>
<P>
	``Separating work and home was something most people aspired  
to,'' says social historian Stephanie Coontz, author of ``The Way 
We Never Were.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Maurice Rovner was a friendly, second-generation immigrant  
beloved in his Baltimore neighborhood. But he soon yearned to live 
away from his hardware store. 
</P>
<P>
	With the business open six days a week until 8 p.m., his wife,  
Stella, had to bring his meals downstairs or mind the store while 
he went up to eat. And there were those Sunday customers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1940s, the family bought a house with a backyard,  
and they felt they'd made it. After that, Maurice brought a little 
bookkeeping home, and his wife occasionally took lunch to the 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	But mostly work stayed at the store, and Sundays were theirs,  
recalls Howard Rovner, the only one of Maurice's sons to make the 
hardware business his life. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1956, when Howard married Naomi, a Baltimore girl who had  
lived over a grocery store as a young girl, she worked as a clerk 
and secretary -- until the children came. 
</P>
<P>
	After that, work was work and home was home.  
</P>
<P>
	``Work was the most important thing. That was my training.  
Business came first,'' says Howard Rovner. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``He was out early in the morning, would come home late, six  
days a week,'' says Dave Rovner, owner of a flourishing computer 
consulting firm, Strategic Network Designs, based in New Jersey, 
far from his Baltimore roots. He's talking about his father, 
Howard. 
</P>
<P>
	It's 1999 now, and Dave Rovner is wheeling his BMW along a  
suburban street, ticking off the ways he squeezes work into his 
day. He totes his cell phone to the golf course. He takes his two 
youngsters to work on Saturdays, where they color while he catches 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	This way, he says, he can work hard yet see his family --  
something he believes his father missed. 
</P>
<P>
	Like his grandfather and father before him, Dave is amiable and  
works very hard. But he has a new confidence, a certainty he's 
controlling his life -- not letting his business control him. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Rovner is a bit bewildered. How can anyone relax if work  
constantly intrudes at home? 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, he understands that his son, as the boss, has to work  
hard. And yet, Howard notes, his son takes his laptop on family 
trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may as well not go on vacation,'' Howard muses.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	One in four households today has a home office, up from one in  
five just two years ago, reports CDB Research &AMP; Consulting. 
</P>
<P>
	True, most Americans still slog to the office or plant -- and  
still fret if they need to slip out for their daughter's soccer 
game. Corporate work-family efforts -- day care, health clubs -- 
often just end up chaining people to the job even more. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why the home office is a powerful symbol of a new way to  
work, a badge of honor in an age when intellectual capital counts 
and time off is better than money. Working at home also promises 
the Great Family-Friendly Life, the balance we yearn for after 
tucking work and home into two separate boxes for most of this 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	At home, you can work in your bathrobe -- ha! to the dress code.  
At home, you can nurse the baby while you work the phones. At home, 
you punch your own clock, right? 
</P>
<P>
	Cutting-edge home buyers think so, and they want offices with  
the best possible techno-gadgets. (Who talks about dens anymore?) 
</P>
<P>
	With this in mind, IBM has paired with a Houston developer to  
build one of the country's first communities with ``networked'' 
homes, meaning they have fast Internet connections, multiple phone 
lines and fully linked computers. 
</P>
<P>
	In their first two weeks on the market, 23 Stone Gate homes were  
sold -- quadruple the rate in traditional developments. Half the 
buyers work at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this is the next frontier,'' says Mary Walker, an  
IBM executive whose title suggests the new direction: general 
manager for home networking. 
</P>
<P>
	Some companies go even further. Regis McKenna did away with all  
permanent offices at his Palo Alto, Calif., consulting firm in 
1997. Now, he and his staff sign up for an office by the day if 
they need one. 
</P>
<P>
	At home, McKenna stops work whenever he likes, to lunch with his  
wife or play with his grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's plenty of time in the 24 hours to intermix all those  
things,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Well ...  
</P>
<P>
	California pharmaceuticals executive Lisa Conte revels in her  
home office: she can tuck her three children, ages 1, 3 and 6, into 
bed, then work for hours. ``If you can get away with not sleeping 
too much, you can have a whole day's work at night,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	The catch? She's exhausted.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still figuring out how to turn it off,'' says Ms. Conte,  
the chief executive officer of Shaman Pharmaceuticals. ``It's such 
a competitive world. Anyone has access to me any time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She is talking with a reporter at 7 a.m., two hours after  
starting work. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not just the boss who's on call. At 15 percent of  
companies, most employees are expected to check voice mail and 
e-mail after hours and during vacations, according to a Conference 
Board study of 62 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet little by little, workers and bosses are setting boundaries.  
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Christian, an executive recruiter who's so plugged in he  
makes phone calls on ski lifts, planned his honeymoon at a resort 
that bans cell phones on the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Drew Neisser, a marketer, blocks off ``down time'' on his  
calendar -- and keeps to it. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Rovner is struggling to draw the line, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a compromise when I integrate family and personal and  
work,'' he says. ``It's challenging to make it work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On vacation now, he only reads the urgent e-mails.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
