<DOCNO> APW19990724.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 15:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Seek Leader After Elway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Shannon Sharpe has the swagger, Terrell  
Davis the statistics, Tyrone Braxton the seniority. Bubby Brister 
has the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Broncos are hoping at least one will be able to  
provide the unspoken leadership that John Elway displayed with his 
cool demeanor, daring downfield scrambles and ultimate success. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, how you become a leader is when you play the game  
well,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``Some people vocally, 
other people just perform well. We need guys to step up where some 
of our leadership is gone. I think we have a nucleus to make that 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Elway's successor, Brister is the obvious choice to assume a  
more prominent role as Denver's on-field leader. Although he will 
be 37 when the Broncos open the season in September, Brister has 
the energy of a caffeine addict and the confidence of a car 
salesman. 
</P>
<P>
	He also has the respect of his teammates after helping the  
Broncos win five games in Elway's absence last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you have a leader like John go down, you always look  
to your quarterback to fill that role,'' defensive end Harald 
Hasselbach said. ``I certainly have every confidence in Bubby. He's 
extremely well-liked by the guys and he commands a lot of 
respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brister also embraces the challenge of being top dog. He has  
been awaiting the opportunity since returning in 1997 from a 
one-year hiatus from football. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one of my strong suits and always has been -- being a  
good leader,'' Brister said Saturday after Denver's first practice 
of training camp, ``but I like to lead by example and not scream 
and holler too much if you don't have to. I'll pick my spots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody leads by example better than Davis, who was named league  
MVP last year after rushing for more than 2,000 yards. Humility, 
however, is one of Davis' best traits. It's not a quality that 
often accompanies a locker room leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty much a quiet-type person when it comes to  
leadership,'' Davis said. ``I don't speak much. I want to go out 
there and just play and hopefully that's enough to encourage 
players who need some leaders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe, on the other hand, rarely meets a run-on sentence he  
doesn't like, and his All-Pro credentials substantiate his 
supercilious nature. It doesn't necessarily mean he's ready to act 
as the team's hall monitor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm probably one of the few guys on offense who will say  
something if I see a guy that's slacking,'' Sharpe said. ``Does 
that make me the leader? No. I'm just going to go out there and do 
my job. I have enough to worry about trying to get Shannon ready to 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On defense, no one has more seniority than Braxton, a safety who  
has spent 12 years in the NFL and 11 with the Broncos. Although not 
as boisterous as Sharpe, the man they call ``Chicken'' isn't afraid 
to prod his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Braxton offers his own candidate, defensive end Alfred Williams.  
</P>
<P>
	``I like Alfred because he's the type of guy who's fun to be  
around but knows when to get serious and take care of business,'' 
Braxton said. ``He has fun, but when it's time for us to go out on 
the field, he does his job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
