<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skinner Happy With All Pocono News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG POND, Pa. (AP) -- Mike Skinner thought he had a decent car,  
so he wasn't certain if he should try to make it better. 
</P>
<P>
	So after practice Friday, he sought out crew chief Larry  
McReynolds, who had already brightened Skinner's outlook by 
announcing he would remain with Richard Childress Racing for the 
next three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Skinner didn't want to make another mistake.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were about an eighth- or 10th-place car after practice,''  
he said. ``I told Larry, I went for all or nothing at Loudon two 
weeks ago, and it bit me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skinner didn't drive a good lap in qualifying for the New  
Hampshire race, and wound up starting 19th. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him to tell me what he wanted to do,'' Skinner said.  
``I told him whatever we did, we'd do it together. He said we're 
going to be together for three years, so let's go for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skinner did just that, and changes in the car resulted in a lap  
of 170.451 mph on the 2 1/2-mile Pocono International Raceway. It gave 
him the third pole of his Winston Cup career. 
</P>
<P>
	It exceeded all expectations, and now Skinner's Chevrolet is the  
car to beat Sunday in the $2.2 million Pennsylvania 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say it was a perfect lap,'' said Skinner, whose  
only other Winston Cup poles came for both Daytona International 
Speedway races as a rookie in 1997. ``But it was a real good one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was in keeping with the spirit of a day in which McReynolds  
announced that in the wake of his ill-fated attempt to start his 
own team he would remain with RCR through 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, I feel like a winner in this deal,'' Skinner said  
of the news on McReynolds. ``I'm pretty pumped up about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also enthusiastic was Mark Martin, whose broken and bent body is  
starting to heel from multiple fractures of three weeks ago. Gone 
is a gait that two weeks ago resembled that of the Hunchback of 
Notre Dame. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great run,'' Martin said after locking up the outside  
of the front row with a lap of 170.078 in a Ford. ``I gave them 
everything I had on that lap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is still recovering from fractures of a knee, wrist and  
rib received three weeks ago in practice for the Pepsi 400 at 
Daytona. A week later, he started 37th and finished sixth in the 
Jiffy Lube 300. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great in the race car,'' he said. ``In New Hampshire, I  
was in pain all over the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Third-fastest was the Chevy of five-time Pocono polesitter Ken  
Schrader at 169.933. He'll start from the most productive position 
on the grid, one that has produced eight victories in 43 Pocono 
races. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope I don't ruin that stat,'' said Schrader -- winless in  
his last 253 starts. ``But that's one of those statistical things 
that don't make much difference when we race Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going from outside of the second row will be the Pontiac of  
Bobby Labonte, the winner last month of the Pocono 500. Labonte's 
lap was run at 169.827. 
</P>
<P>
	He thought he could have been faster, but never found the ideal  
combination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just needed to be a little tighter,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't Sterling Marlin's problem. He established the track  
qualifying record with a run last month at 170.506, and was the 
fastest Friday in both practice sessions before qualifying ninth in 
his Chevy at 169.444. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tightened the car up a little bit from practice,'' he said.  
``But the clouds were out, and we were a little too tight in turn 
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth-fastest was the Pontiac of John Andretti. Then came the  
Chevys of Hendrick Motorsports teammates Wally Dallenbach and Jeff 
Gordon. Ward Burton was eighth in a Pontiac, followed by Marlin and 
the Chevy of Joe Nemechek. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying 15th in a Ford was series points leader Dale Jarrett.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
