<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 10:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Leaguer Sees a Big Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Craig Paquette's baseball experience  
has taken him from the major leagues to the Triple-A stops a notch 
below, where the players aren't quite as good, the perks not quite 
as lavish. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, at age 30, Paquette find himself in a different uniform,  
playing a brand of baseball that is, in some ways, a throwback to 
his earliest days in the game. It's certainly not as glamorous, but 
that's OK with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can anybody turn this down?'' says Paquette, the cleanup  
hitter on the United States Pan Am baseball team, his nation's 
first to use professional players in international competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people at (Class AAA) Norfolk notified me that I had the  
opportunity and I found out it was a great chance to play for your 
country and be seen by a lot of other people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Paquette was the Kansas City Royals' starting  
third baseman, one season after establishing career highs with 22 
homers and 67 RBIs. But hitting slumps and then ankle surgery after 
signing with the New York Mets have limited his time in the majors 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	He's still got 426 major league games and 55 big league homers  
to his credit. He's becoming reacquainted with his baseball 
beginnings and hoping he can address his future with a good 
showing. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's different.  
</P>
<P>
	During practice games leading up to the Pan Am competition that  
begins Sunday, the USA team didn't find the clubhouse food spreads 
that awaits professional players, especially those in the majors. 
There wasn't even a clubhouse at one locale. 
</P>
<P>
	So Paquette and his teammates wolfed down fast food before the  
game and changed from practice to game uniforms in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most guys where anticipating this any way,'' said USA  
teammate Jason Hardtke, who has seen limited time in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here to play baseball and that's all that matters,''  
Paquette said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of this is new for everybody. We only have one or two  
guys competing who've been in international play. I've never been 
in single elimination games before. No doubt there is a lot of 
pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Team USA must finish in the top two or fail to qualify for the  
Sydney Olympics next year. They must do so against a talented field 
that includes seven-time defending Pan Am baseball champion Cuba 
and the Dominican Republic, which beat the USA twice in a warmup 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Paquette can DH, play first or the outfield, but mostly he's  
being counted on to provide punch for a team that doesn't have a 
lot of power. Leadership, too, for a mix of veterans and young 
pros, none of whom are on 40-man major league rosters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of the guys look up to Craig because he's been  
around and got a lot of time in the majors,'' Hardtke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the U.S. does qualify for the Olympics, there's a good  
chance many of the players currently in Winnipeg won't be making 
the long trip to Australia. Why? They hope by that time to be 
called to the majors, or in Paquette's case, be called back up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I can still play in the big leagues, it's a matter of  
getting a chance,'' Paquette said. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll return to Norfolk once the Pan Am baseball competition  
ends and then take it from there. Finish out the Triple-A schedule 
and maybe get a late-season call from the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what's going on,'' he said. ``I don't even pay  
attention to it anymore. I'm tired of it. I don't worry what's 
happening up there and I don't even look at the box scores 
anymore,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is play baseball and take advantage of it. Just  
like playing for your country. You get the chance and you take 
advantage of it, too.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 12:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball's Richest Pitchers Meet Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- At first glance, Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown,  
baseball's richest pitchers, would seem to be experiencing similar 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has a 10-7 record. Brown is 10-6.  
</P>
<P>
	Yet, as they prepared for a Sunday night showdown, their third  
since last October, their true fates have been vastly different. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson leads the NL in earned run average at 2.65 and the  
majors in strikeouts with 229. He is a legitimate threat to break 
Nolan Ryan's single-season strikeout record of 383. If not for a 
four-game stretch when he pitched great but lost because his 
Arizona teammates failed to provide him with even one run, Johnson 
could easily be 14-3. And, most significantly, his team is 
contending for the NL West title. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could make the case for Randy maybe having one of the best  
years of his career with the exception of those games he should 
have won,'' manager Buck Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least on the surface, Johnson has coped with his team's  
inability to provide him with any help. The Diamondbacks finally 
came through for him in a 6-0 shutout in his triumphant return to 
Seattle last Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I'm trying to do out there is put the team in  
position to win,'' Johnson said. ``It doesn't matter what pitcher 
I'm facing. I've got a job to do and that's to keep the runs to a 
minimum, and our hitters have a job to do and that's to score runs. 
If we both do our jobs, good things happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, meanwhile, has a 3.79 ERA with 127 strikeouts, third in  
the NL but 102 fewer than Johnson. Brown has had some strong games, 
and some awful ones. After allowing just eight homers all of last 
season with San Diego, he has given up 15 this year. Los Angeles, 
the team that counted on him to lead it to the NL West crown, has 
nose-dived into last place, 10 games below .500. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a year where it seems like someone is trying to test  
me,'' Brown said after his last outing, an 8-4 victory over 
Pittsburgh. ``It's been that way the whole year. Game after game, 
it's like a witch doctor has a curse on me. If anybody knows how to 
get rid of it, tell him to send it to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing for sure, both pitchers will be intense Sunday. It's  
their trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one thing that I respect and appreciate in his game is  
that he goes about his business much like I do,'' Johnson said. 
``Maybe it's not the best way, but it's the best way for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two pitchers first squared off last October in the NL  
divisional playoffs, an outstanding duel that ended with Brown's 
Padres beating Johnson and the Houston Astros 2-1. Both became 
highly-sought free agents after last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson signed a four-year, $52.4 million contract with the  
Arizona Diamondbacks. Twelve days later, Brown signed an amazing 
seven-year, $105 million deal with Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April 5, on opening day, they were the starting pitchers as  
the Diamondbacks played at Dodger Stadium. Another close, 
low-scoring game? Hardly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously they're the premier pitchers in the league,''  
Dodgers' catcher Todd Hundley said. ``Opening day everyone was 
expecting a pitcher's duel, and look what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks got five runs on 10 hits off Brown in 5 2-3  
innings. Johnson pitched well, and left after seven innings with a 
5-2 lead. But, as would be the case many more times in the coming 
weeks, Arizona's bullpen couldn't hold on, and Los Angeles came 
back to win 8-6 in 11 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday night probably won't be the last time the two will face  
off this season. If the rotation stays intact, Johnson and Brown 
will be the starters next Friday night at Dodger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, though, said he never thinks about his opposing  
pitcher. Everybody seems to mount their best effort when they know 
he's pitching, he said. Jose Jimenez of St. Louis, who beat Johnson 
and the Diamondbacks with a 1-0 no-hitter, is a classic example. 
</P>
<P>
	``A pitching matchup is one thing, but I'm not facing him,''  
Johnson said. ``I'm facing his lineup. I can only worry about 
facing those eight guys that are coming up to the plate. It doesn't 
matter who I'm pitching against. What's the worse that Kevin 
Brown's going to do on Sunday? Shut me out? Like I haven't had that 
happen.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 13:14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Aerospace Firms Near Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler Aerospace and France's  
Aerospatiale Matra are close to agreement on a merger deal that 
would create the world's biggest aerospace company after Boeing, a 
newsmagazine reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel said the plans to fuse the two companies are already  
on the desk of French President Jacques Chirac, who must approve 
any deal involving the aerospace and defense group Aerospatiale 
Matra, which is 48 percent state-owned. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsmagazine said the deal was worked out by DaimlerChrysler  
chairman Juergen Schrempp and Jean Luc Legardere, chairman of 
Aerospatiale Matra's supervisory board. The report did not cite 
sources. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, Rainer Ohler, would  
neither confirm nor deny the report. ``Everybody's talking with 
everybody,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Aerospatiale Matra in Paris declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Der Spiegel's report is the latest in a flurry of consolidation  
announcements from Europe's aerospace and defense industry, which 
has said it hopes to better compete against U.S. giants like Boeing 
and Lockheed Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	European companies already cooperate in building Airbus  
commercial planes and Eurofighter and Tornado military jets, but 
industry insiders fear that unless they pool their skills, finances 
and research more closely, they will be picked off by U.S. firms 
keen to expand into European markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last month, DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, known as Dasa,  
signed a memo of understanding with Spain's Construcciones 
Aeronauticas SA to merge into Europe's first multinational 
aerospace company, beating out Aerospatiale Matra and other 
European firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Dasa earlier this month announced a joint venture in space  
technology with Aerospatiale Matra and the Marconi division of 
Britain's General Electric Co. The Alenia Spazio division of 
Italy's Finmeccanica is expected to join that venture, called 
astrium, later. 
</P>
<P>
	In both deals, Dasa officials said the aim was to strengthen  
competitiveness and contribute to ``European industrial 
integration.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
