<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 19:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Langston Has Yankee Nightmare Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Talk about horror films.  
</P>
<P>
	When Mark Langston walked out to the mound at Yankee Stadium on  
Saturday, he saw a videotape of a night he'd rather forget: Tino 
Martinez's grand slam off him in Game 1 of last year's World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Langston gave up nine runs in his worst outing in 11 years  
as Cleveland lost to the New York Yankees 21-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre was livid, immediately calling  
upstairs for an explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The New York Yankees should be above that,'' Torre said.  
</P>
<P>
	Even before he talked about the win, the Yankees' biggest in 46  
years, Torre wanted to send a message to Langston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just thought it was in bad taste,'' Torre said. ``I have no  
idea who was responsible for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego led the Yankees, an overwhelming favorite, 5-2 in the  
fifth inning of Game 1 last Oct. 17 before Chuck Knoblauch's 
three-run homer off Donne Wall. 
</P>
<P>
	With the bases loaded, Langston went to a 2-2 count on Martinez  
and thought he threw a called third strike by him, but plate umpire 
Richie Garcia called it a ball. Martinez then homered for a 9-5 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing is, they didn't show the 2-2 pitch,'' Langston  
said, showing a sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
	After the video, Langston walked Chuck Knoblauch and fell down  
trying to field Derek Jeter's bunt, which went for a single. 
</P>
<P>
	Two outs later, Chili Davis hit a two-run single that center  
fielder Kenny Lofton nearly came up with on an attempted diving 
catch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all kind of fell apart from there,'' Langston (1-1) said.  
</P>
<P>
	He allowed nine runs -- seven earned -- and 10 hits in 4 1-3  
innings. It was the most runs off him since Oakland scored nine on 
April 29, 1988, when he was with Seattle. It was the most hits he 
allowed since Detroit got 10 on April 19, 1997, when he was with 
Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, my stuff wasn't that good,'' Langston said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
