<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Female Shuttle Chief Busy in Orbit  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The first woman to command an  
American rocketship, Eileen Collins, was ``extremely happy'' when 
she and her crew reached orbit yesterday, but even happier when 
they sent the $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory on its 
five-year voyage to search for black holes and peer at galaxies, 
quasars and exploded stars. The 42-year-old Air Force colonel said 
she has been so busy in orbit that she hasn't had time to think 
about her new spot in space history. ``We still have a few more 
days, so the pressure isn't off yet,'' Collins said today from 
space shuttle Columbia. 

</P>
<P>
	Bessette Memorial Held in Conn.  
</P>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Hundreds of friends and family paid  
their last respects to Lauren Bessette and her sister Carolyn who 
perished with John F. Kennedy Jr. in a plane crash in waters off 
Martha's Vineyard. At a private memorial, the two sisters were 
remembered as bright young women with promising futures. The 
candlelight service was held in the name of Lauren -- the ``other 
Bessette,'' the victim the world knew least -- although prayers were 
also offered for Carolyn and John. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Slayings To Be Investigated  
</P>
<P>
	GRACKO, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The chief prosecutor of the Yugoslav  
war crimes tribunal ordered today an investigation into the slaying 
of 14 Serbs. The prosecutor, Louise Arbour, said a message of 
deterrence must be sent to those who perpetuate the violence that 
has shattered Kosovo in the last year. The victims were found by a 
NATO patrol after automatic weapons fire was heard in a field near 
this town 10 miles south of Pristina, the capital. No suspects were 
immediately identified. 

</P>
<P>
	Moroccans Mourn King Hassan  
</P>
<P>
	RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Moroccans mourned their king with mounting  
vigor today, standing silently outside the old walled palace where 
Hassan II reigned for two generations as spiritual leader, chief 
executive officer and godfather. By evening, the crowds at the 
palace swelled into many thousands. More discreetly, other 
Moroccans expressed harsher judgments of the king's grip on power, 
which remained firm to the end despite relaxing some since 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	15 Hurt in Gay Pride Parade Attack  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A tear-gas canister was thrown into the crowd  
watching a Lesbian and Gay Pride parade today, injuring more than a 
dozen people. No arrests were made. About 15 people were treated at 
the scene for eye and skin irritations. Three others, including a 
woman with asthma, were taken to a local hospital with minor 
injuries. 

</P>
<P>
	Canadian Nurses Call Off Strike  
</P>
<P>
	LAVAL, Quebec (AP) -- Quebec's 47,500 striking nurses announced  
today they would end a four-week walkout while they seek mediation 
in the dispute. Jennie Skene, president of the Quebec Federation of 
Nurses, said nurses would return to work immediately while union 
leaders consult with outside parties and re-evaluate their options. 
The nurses, who walked off the job on June 26, say they're among 
the most poorly paid in Canada. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Train Derails, Injures 16  
</P>
<P>
	RENSSELAER, N.Y. (AP) -- Sixteen passengers were injured after an  
Amtrak passenger train partially derailed this afternoon. Three 
cars slipped off the tracks when the train slammed into another 
train it was attempting to hook up with, witnesses said. Twelve 
passengers and four crew members of the ``Lakeshore Limited'' were 
taken to local hospitals. 

</P>
<P>
	30,000 People Form Euro 2004 Logo  
</P>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- More than 30,000 people formed a human  
logo in the shape of a soccer player today at Lisbon's National 
Stadium to promote Portugal's bid to host the 2004 European 
championship. Sporting colored hoods, the crowd assembled in the 
silhouette of a player next to stripes of red and green, the colors 
of Portugal's flag. The words `Portugal, 2004' and `Euro' were 
etched on the stripes. Among the participants was Prime Minister 
Antonio Guterres. 

</P>
<P>
	Woodstock Fans Try To Stay Cool  
</P>
<P>
	ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- At Woodstock '99 heat exhaustion and  
dehydration continued to be the top concern as more than 225,000 
people sweltered in 90-degree-plus temperatures. Organizers 
encouraged people to drink lots of water today, the second day of 
the three-day megaconcert. Since the concert began, emergency 
medical crews had treated nearly 1,000 people for heat exhaustion 
and dehydration. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Nears Tour de France Win  
</P>
<P>
	FUTUROSCOPE, France (AP) -- With one stage to go, a final  
triumphant ride from Arpajon to the grand Champs-Elysees in Paris, 
the Tour de France all but belongs to American Lance Armstrong. The 
Texan covered today's 35-mile segment in 1 hour, 8 minutes, 17 
seconds -- 9 seconds ahead of Alex Zulle of Switzerland, who moved 
into second place in the overall standings. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
