<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 16:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stellar Brush Captures Ohio Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH RANDALL, Ohio (AP) -- Stellar Brush overtook the field  
around the turn and held off Ecton Park by a neck to win the 
$300,000 Ohio Derby at Thistledown on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stellar Brush went 1 1/8 miles in 1:49 1-5 and paid $9.60, $3.80  
and $3. Ecton Park paid $3.20 and $2.80 while Valhol, 
three-quarters of a length back in third, paid $5.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Stellar Brush, sired by 1986 Ohio Derby winner Broad Brush, ran  
in the back of the pack early, made a move on the turn to gain a 
contending position, then charged into the lead with a quarter-mile 
to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a terrific course,'' said Richard Small, who has also  
trained a second- and a third-place finisher in previous Ohio 
Derbys. ``We couldn't be more pleased. We were lucky to have 
(jockey) Michael McCarthy give up some good rides at Delaware Park 
to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stellar Brush opened the day at 9-2 and was bet down to 7-2 by  
post time. He won the $200,000 Leonard Richards at Delaware Park 
earlier this year and also was second in the $200,000 Iowa Derby at 
Prairie Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sky's led through six furlongs before fading to fourth.  
Grits'n Hard Toast and Millions battled near the lead much of the 
race and then weakened. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is definitely a pinnacle for my career,'' McCarthy said.  
``I've been here before, but never on such a huge scale. Our horse 
was a little excited before the race because I think he just wanted 
to get in and get it over with. He settled nicely after he broke 
from the gate and responded when I needed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stellar Brush claimed a $180,000 purse by besting 12 rivals.  
</P>
<P>
	The Derby is the first leg of the $1 Million DeBartolo Racing  
Challenge, which includes the Remington Park Derby on Sept. 5 and 
the Super Derby at Louisiana Downs on Oct. 2. Any horse winning all 
three events receives a $1 million bonus. Horses running in all 
three races are eligible for various participation bonuses totaling 
$300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Small said he wasn't sure whether Stellar Brush would race in  
the Remington Park Derby. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 04:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slim Evidence Against SLA Fugitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- No eyewitnesses link former fugitive Kathleen  
Soliah to a police bombing plot and the most damaging witnesses 
against her are dead, according to newly released transcripts from 
her 23-year-old case. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Soliah planted the bombs as a member of the  
radical Symbionese Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 27 witnesses testified before the federal grand jury  
that indicted Soliah, a plumbing contractor and a bomb expert 
provided the strongest links to materials used in the 1975 attacks, 
according to 1976 transcripts released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men have since died.  
</P>
<P>
	Soliah, now a 52-year-old doctor's wife and Minnesota mother of  
three, could face life in prison if convicted of conspiracy to kill 
Los Angeles police with nail bombs that were placed under two 
patrol cars. Neither bomb went off. 
</P>
<P>
	Soliah, who now calls herself Sara Jane Olson, has pleaded  
innocent. She was freed Tuesday on $1 million bail after spending 
five weeks in jail following her arrest in Minnesota. She arrived 
at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport on Friday night, 
and did not meet with reporters or supporters waiting to greet her. 
</P>
<P>
	She has admitted fleeing two decades ago after her indictment.  
</P>
<P>
	The 236-page grand jury transcript records the testimony of  
witnesses, most of them law enforcement officers, who told how the 
pipe bombs were discovered under police cars -- one in the parking 
lot of a restaurant and one at a police station. 
</P>
<P>
	Bomb experts explained in detail the components of the bombs and  
the flaws that kept them from detonating and other experts told of 
the grave injuries that would have occurred if they exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	Police claimed that the bombs were intended as retaliation for  
the 1974 SLA shootout in which Los Angeles officers killed six 
members of the radical underground group. 
</P>
<P>
	A former San Francisco policeman and freelance photographer told  
of hearing Soliah speak at a Berkeley rally shortly after the 
shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander Jason identified Soliah from a photo. He testified  
that he heard her speak of the death of her friend Angela Atwood, 
who was killed in the shootout, and express support for William and 
Emily Harris and Patricia Hearst, known as Tania, who were then 
wanted by the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember her saying, 'Tania, Emily, and Bill ... you have  
made your message clear. Keep fighting,''' Jason testified. ``She 
said, 'Keep fighting. We are with you. I am with you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Plumbing company employee James Marshall identified Soliah from  
a photograph as the woman who accompanied a man who bought 
materials linked to the pipe bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb expert, Arleigh McCree, said he thought the bombs could  
have been made in an apartment in San Francisco where Soliah's 
fingerprints were found. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah's lawyer, Stuart Hanlon, noted that the FBI and  
police department experts were unable to match prints on the bombs 
to any SLA members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wouldn't that make you think they have the wrong group of  
people?'' Hanlon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless further evidence is uncovered, the case should be  
dismissed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Michael Latin has acknowledged the circumstantial  
nature of the case but has said there is sufficient evidence to 
bring her to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Soliah's fingerprints were found in a San Francisco apartment  
rented by the Harrises. Authorities said a closet full of 
bombmaking materials and weapons were found in the apartment, along 
with a gun manual and an Army technical manual. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the transcript, experts found Soliah's prints on  
the gun manual and the apartment walls. 
</P>
<P>
	However, McCree, who examined the police car bombs and a bomb  
found in the closet, was the only expert who testified that the 
three devices positively were connected, based on their materials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some individual who had access to those materials did build  
these three bombs,'' McCree testified. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
