<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Perez Pulled From Rotation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Carlos Perez was removed from the Los Angeles  
Dodgers' pitching rotation and second baseman Eric Young was given 
at least a few days off as manager Davey Johnson tries to shore up 
his slumping team. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez (2-10) gave up 10 runs on 11 hits in six innings in the  
Dodgers' 10-1 loss to the Arizona Diamondbacks Friday night. The 
27-year-old right-hander, acquired in a seven-player trade with 
Montreal a year ago, has a 7.43 ERA, worst among Dodgers starters. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday night's debacle clinched Johnson's decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants to work at it, I'm sure he can get it back,''  
Johnson said. ``But I can't keep going through that. He took it 
pretty hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he will decide by Sunday who will take Perez's  
place in the rotation next Wednesday against Cincinnati. He 
mentioned five possibilities, including two relievers on the 
big-league roster -- Jamie Arnold and Onan Masaoka. Arnold (2-2) has 
two starts this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson also said he was considering two pitchers with Triple-A  
Albuquerque, Mike Judd and Robinson Checo, and Eric Gagne, pitching 
for Double-A San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Young will sit because various leg ailments have  
hampered his defense. Young's failure to turn a routine double play 
Friday night cleared the way for Arizona's five-run fourth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it is footwork and timing,'' Johnson said. ``If  
you're not 100 percent, you're going to get killed down there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he would wait to see how Young feels early next  
week to determine whether to put him back in the lineup. Meanwhile, 
Jose Vizcaino and Craig Counsell will platoon at second. Vizcaino 
was in the starting lineup Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson brushed aside any concern over Raul Mondesi's behavior  
Friday night. After the five-run inning, Mondesi didn't go back to 
the dugout, instead of spending the Dodgers' time at-bat in the 
bullpen chatting with relief pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan to talk to him to find out what was going on,'' Johnson  
said. ``I don't take a head count in the dugout. For all I know, he 
had to go to the bathroom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi has declined to discuss the incident.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
