<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Flock to Hemingway's Haunts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PETOSKEY, Mich. (AP) -- Although Judy Henn was raised in New York  
and lived in Israel for 31 years, there was no question in her mind 
she was in the right place Saturday as she trudged along the muddy 
two-track forest road in northern Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am a genuine, certified Ernest Hemingway nut,'' Ms. Henn  
said, fanning herself with a sheaf of papers on which she has 
scrawled copious notes while visiting sites linked with the 
author's early days. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 20-minute walk along the path, Ms. Henn paused beside a  
clearing overgrown with waist-high grass. This was the Indian camp 
referred to in several of the Nick Adams stories, a guide explained 
to the group Ms. Henn was with. 
</P>
<P>
	She gazed at the spot.  
</P>
<P>
	``Being in places like this gives you a sense of what he saw,  
what he felt,'' she said. ``It's a heady experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 fans have flocked to Petoskey and neighboring Horton  
Bay this week for a Hemingway centennial festival. Born July 21, 
1899, he spent his first 16 summers at the family cottage on 
Walloon Lake. Many of his short stories and the novella ``The 
Torrents of Spring'' are set in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsored by the Michigan Hemingway Society and the Little  
Traverse Bay Historical Society, this week's events have given the 
faithful -- from the United States and countries ranging from 
England to Japan -- a chance to retrace the writer's boyhood 
footsteps. 
</P>
<P>
	Some are academics, such as Ms. Henn, who is writing a doctoral  
dissertation on ``The Torrents of Spring.'' Others are aspiring 
writers. Still others simply admire the man and his work. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wrote about the kinds of things we did as kids -- fishing,  
hunting, playing in the woods, and he did it so vividly it all 
comes to life again,'' said Karen Moberg of Rapid River. ``You can 
feel it and taste it and smell it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Bourke, who teaches a Hemingway course at a college in the  
Canadian province of Alberta, was among a group that attended a 
conference in the author's hometown of Oak Park, Ill., before 
heading to Petoskey. 
</P>
<P>
	``This helps provide that sense of place that's so important to  
understand Hemingway's writing,'' Bourke said after touring 
Windemere, the Hemingway cottage on Walloon Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Busloads of tourists arrived throughout the week to see the  
cottage, which owner Ernest Mainland -- the author's nephew -- opened 
to the public for the occasion. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's something romantic about visiting places where great  
artists walked,'' said David Bardallis of Midland, who works for 
the Mackinac Center for Public Policy, a conservative think tank in 
Midland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
