<HEADLINE> Redskins, Top Pick Agree on Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- The Washington Redskins today reached a  
verbal agreement with first-round draft pick Champ Bailey, The 
Associated Press has learned. 
</P>
<P>
	Team sources speaking on condition of anonymity said Bailey  
agreed to a five-year deal and the contract could be signed in time 
for Bailey to report to the first day of training camp in 
Frostburg, Md., on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Times reported today the deal was worth $10.25  
million over five years and includes a $5.2 million signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins had been seeking a five-year contract while  
Bailey's agent had been looking for a four-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey was the seventh overall selection in the April draft. He  
played cornerback and wide receiver at Georgia and is expected to 
start at cornerback opposite Darrell Green for the Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Norv Turner said this week that if Bailey reported to camp  
on time there would be a chance that he also could play on offense 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey's signing was the latest aggressive move by new team  
owner Daniel Snyder, who closed his $800 million purchase of the 
team earlier this month. On Friday, Snyder removed Charley Casserly 
as general manager and made him a ``consultant to the owner.'' 
Vinny Serrato was appointed director of player personnel, assuming 
most of Casserly's duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, it appeared negotiations with Bailey would  
not be resolved until several days into training camp. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
