<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> African Queen Offering Rides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAY CITY, Mich. (AP) -- The boat that once carted Humphrey Bogart  
and Katharine Hepburn around on the silver screen is plying 
Michigan waters. 
</P>
<P>
	The African Queen, from the movie of the same name, will offer  
rides on the Saginaw River as a fund-raiser for the Saginaw Valley 
Naval Ship Museum Committee. A half-hour cruise on the boat built 
in 1912 costs $15. The rides will last until Aug. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The boat is captained by James Hendricks, 75, a retired Kentucky  
attorney who bought the vessel in 1982 for $65,000 because, ``I was 
trying to find something respectable to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hendricks, a fan of Hepburn, also owns two boats used in another  
of her movies, ``On Golden Pond.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bogart and Hepburn were on the boat when they filmed their movie  
in Africa. Hendricks said in the early 1980s he exchanged letters 
with Hepburn and asked her if she would like to ride on The African 
Queen once more. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said she thought it blew up in Africa,'' Hendricks  
recalled. He was never able to get Hepburn on board. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
