<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Blaze in Nevada, California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- More than 400 firefighters battled a blaze  
that charred 10,000 acres of sagebrush and pines, burned within 
one-half mile of a major highway and sent a large column of smoke 
billowing in the sky Saturday just east of Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	Other fires had blackened 32,000 acres in the state's northeast  
corner and 17,000 acres near Naval Air Station Fallon. 
</P>
<P>
	A blaze in California had spread across 13,700 acres.  
</P>
<P>
	The column of smoke was clearly visible from downtown Reno as  
flames spread through steep canyons near Lockwood, about eight 
miles east of Reno and within one-half mile south of Interstate 80. 
Wind carried the smoke away from the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's mostly a hand-crew operation and they've been hiking in  
the dark in rough terrain,'' Forest Service spokeswoman Jocelyn 
Biro said Saturday. Four firefighters were treated for knee and 
ankle injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire was estimated at about 50 percent contained at one  
point, but officials backed that off to 35 percent later in the day 
after the flames crossed a ridge and burned closer to the 
interstate. 
</P>
<P>
	The highway remained open but authorities warned motorists to  
watch for fire equipment driving through the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of travelers stopped along the road Saturday afternoon to  
watch the flames and the helicopters dipping huge buckets on cables 
into a river to scoop up water to dump on the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	It started Friday and the cause was under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's still burning pretty good. It's not just one flame front.  
We have pretty good activity in three or four areas,'' Biro said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters were confident the Truckee River running along the  
south side of I-80 would keep the fire from jumping the highway, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	No buildings were threatened.  
</P>
<P>
	The fire 30 miles southeast of Fallon, a town 60 miles east of  
Reno, was about 50 percent contained Saturday, said federal fire 
command post spokeswoman Heidi Netzler. 
</P>
<P>
	That blaze was started Thursday by bombs dropped by Navy planes  
on a training range at Naval Air Station Fallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were prepared to evacuate the town of Middlegate  
late Friday, but Netzler said a shift in the wind made an 
evacuation unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters also were at work Saturday on a fire that had  
burned 32,000 acres in the sparsely settled northeast corner of 
Nevada and into Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears they've got that one pretty much handled,'' said  
Bob Knutson of the Great Western Great Basin fire center in Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the West, a 13,700-acre fire in California's Santa  
Barbara County had been 75 percent surrounded, and full containment 
was expected Sunday evening, said county fire department Capt. 
Charlie Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,800 firefighters worked on the six-day-old blaze  
Saturday, contending with erratic wind and temperatures in the 90s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990724.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 03:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It took the Houston Astros more than five weeks to win this one.  
</P>
<P>
	Manager Larry Dierker and the Astros finally finished their  
suspended game against the San Diego Padres on Friday night, 
winning 4-3 behind the grand slam Derek Bell hit June 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros then won their scheduled game against the Padres 7-4,  
behind Matt Mieske's grand slam. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker caused the suspended game when he collapsed in the  
dugout from a seizure. He had brain surgery two days later to 
repair abnormal blood vessels and returned last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had this one logged as a win, although I knew anything could  
happen,'' Dierker said after the opener. ``I've been counting this 
win for about a month now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Reynolds (11-7) got the victory without throwing a pitch  
Friday and Heath Murray (0-2) got the loss without being present. 
Murray (0-2), who allowed the grand slam, started for Triple-A Las 
Vegas on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Wagner pitched the ninth for his 24th save despite  
allowing solo homers to Phil Nevin and Ruben Rivera. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything more had happened, I might have had another  
seizure and Shane might have had one with me,'' Dierker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mieske's third career slam broke an eighth-inning tie as Houston  
rallied against Donne Wall (6-2) in the second game. Mike Hampton 
(13-3) pitched his third complete game of the season, allowing 
eight hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't here when Derek hit his,'' said Mieske, obtained June  
20 from Seattle. ``So that makes it kind of neat that we won both 
games on grand slam homers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other NL games, it was Philadelphia 6, Atlanta 5 in the first  
game; Atlanta 3, Philadelphia 1, in the second game; Montreal 5, 
Pittsburgh 1; Florida 5, Milwaukee 4; New York 5, Chicago 4; St. 
Louis 6, Colorado 4; Arizona 10, Los Angeles 1; and San Francisco 
6, Cincinnati 5. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Phillies 6, Braves 5, 1st game    	
</P>
<P>
                    *Braves 3, Phillies 1, 2nd game    	
</P>
<P>
	In Philadelphia, Kevin Jordan went 2-for-4 with three RBIs,  
including a key two-run single, as the Phillies rallied from a 
five-run deficit to win the opener of a doubleheader with Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Bruce Chen allowed one run in 7 2-3 innings and Bret  
Boone broke an eighth-inning tie when he scored on a wild pitch as 
the Braves won the second game. 
</P>
<P>
	While Philadelphia has won six of nine, the Braves have lost six  
of eight. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Expos 5, Pirates 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Javier Vazquez pitched a four-hitter to become the first  
Montreal starter in nearly a month to win as the Expos scored five 
in the top of the first inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Vazquez (3-5) got his first career complete game to stop  
Montreal's three-game losing streak and extend the Pirates' losing 
streak to five. 
</P>
<P>
	Vazquez posted the first win by an Expos starter since Carl  
Pavano beat Florida on June 25. Montreal starters were 0-11 with a 
6.38 ERA in a 23-game winless stretch that tied the team record set 
in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Ritchie (9-7) took the loss.  
</P>
<P>
                        *Marlins 5, Brewers 4    	
</P>
<P>
	In Miami, Jorge Fabregas' two-out single in the ninth inning  
completed a comeback by Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Trailing 4-2 in the eighth, the Marlins moved within a run when  
Bob Wickman (2-5) walked a batter with the bases loaded. A wild 
throw in the ninth helped the Marlins win on RBI singles by Mark 
Kotsay and Fabregas. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir Nunez (4-3) pitched a scoreless ninth for his first win  
since being traded from Arizona to the Marlins for Matt Mantei. 
</P>
<P>
                           *Mets 5, Cubs 4    	
</P>
<P>
	Mike Piazza's two-out single broke a seventh-inning tie at New  
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Benny Agbayani's two-out, two-run triple tied it in the sixth  
for the Mets, who have won seven of nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Cook (8-2) pitched a perfect seventh for the victory.  
Cubs starter Kevin Tapani (6-7) has not won since June 24 at 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Sammy Sosa hit his major league-leading 35th homer for the  
Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Cardinals 6, Rockies 4    	
</P>
<P>
	In Denver, Mark McGwire hit his 34th home run, one short of  
major league-leader Sammy Sosa, as St. Louis ended Colorado's 
three-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, 2-for-4 with a walk, has homered in seven of his last  
nine games. Rookie Joe McEwing went 3-for-4 with a solo homer and 
two RBIs for the Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Darren Oliver (5-7), 0-5 with four no-decisions in nine previous  
starts, allowed two runs and eight hits in eight innings. Roberto 
Ramirez (1-2) took the loss. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Diamondbacks 10, Dodgers 1    	
</P>
<P>
	In Phoenix, Matt Williams hit his 24th home run and six other  
Diamondbacks doubled as Arizona won its fourth in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Bell was 2-for-3 with three RBIs and Luis Gonzalez went  
2-for-4 with two RBIs for the Diamondbacks, who hadn't won four 
straight since June 16. Eight of Arizona's runs came with two outs. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Daal and Byung-Hyun Kim combined on a two-hitter. Daal  
(9-5) allowed one run -- Gary Sheffield's solo homer in the sixth -- 
on two hits through seven innings. Los Angeles' Carlos Perez (2-10) 
gave up all 10 runs and 11 hits through six innings. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Giants 6, Reds 5    	
</P>
<P>
	In San Francisco, Ellis Burks walked twice with the bases  
loaded, driving in the tie-breaking run in the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Servais also drew a bases-loaded walk to give San  
Francisco three runs from walks. 
</P>
<P>
	The win, just the third in the past 10 games for San Francisco,  
kept the Giants a half-game in front of Arizona in the NL West. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Spradlin (3-1) threw a scoreless seventh for the victory.  
Scott Sullivan (3-2) took the loss. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
