<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	David Cone didn't have to be perfect for the New York Yankees to  
beat the Cleveland Indians. They did need a perfectly placed hit by 
Derek Jeter, though. 
</P>
<P>
	While Cone failed to approach his perfect-game performance  
against Montreal, the Yankees beat Cleveland 9-8 in 10 innings 
Friday night thanks to Jeter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees' All-Star shortstop came through with the winning  
hit when he sliced a two-out, two-run single with the bases loaded 
beyond the reach of right fielder Manny Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't fun for me until the last at-bat,'' said Jeter, who  
was 0-for-5 with three strikeouts before his winning hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitching for the first time since his perfect game Sunday, Cone  
started Friday night's game at Yankee Stadium by walking Kenny 
Lofton. Against the Expos, Cone never allowed any batter as many as 
three balls. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Cone lasted only four innings and allowed six runs,  
two of them earned. He made 104 pitches, 16 more than he threw 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not a very good encore,'' he said. ``I was really pumped up. I  
was probably a little overly excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the AL, it was Toronto 2, Chicago 1; Texas 11,  
Tampa Bay 8; Baltimore 1, Anaheim 0; Detroit 14, Boston 5; 
Minnesota 5, Seattle 4; and Kansas City 12, Oakland 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Alomar hit a grand slam off Cone and started a  
sensational double play for the Indians. Still, the Yankees moved 
past Cleveland for the best record in the majors -- it's the first 
time this year the World Series champions (58-37) have had the top 
mark. 
</P>
<P>
	New York won its fourth in a row overall and eighth straight in  
extra innings. The Indians (58-38) have lost seven of eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Enrique Wilson's RBI single with two outs in the 10th off Jason  
Grimsley (7-1) put Cleveland ahead 8-7. Mike Jackson (3-4) then 
gave up a single and two walks before allowing Jeter's hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't afford to walk guys,'' Jackson said. ``For some  
reason, I couldn't get the ball down.'' 
</P>
<P>
                       *Blue Jays 2, White Sox 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Mike Matheny hit a two-run homer in the fifth at Chicago to lead  
Toronto to its seventh straight win. 
</P>
<P>
	Joey Hamilton (3-5) entered the game with a 7.58 ERA, but held  
the White Sox scoreless until Frank Thomas' 13th homer in the 
seventh made it 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Shawn Green extended his hitting streak to a career-high 21  
games with a first-inning double off Jim Parque (9-6). Green tied 
Thomas and the Orioles' B.J. Surhoff for the AL's longest hitting 
streak this season. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Rangers 11, Devil Rays 8    	
</P>
<P>
	Todd Zeile hit a three-run homer and Danny Kolb got his first  
major league victory as Texas won at Tampa Bay, the Rangers' sixth 
straight victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers, 8-1 despite homering in just three games since the  
All-Star break, homered four times. Lee Stevens and Ivan Rodriguez 
added two-run homers and Rusty Greer hit a solo shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Kolb (1-0), in his first appearance since being recalled from  
Triple-A Oklahoma City on Tuesday, replaced injured starter Mike 
Morgan to start the third. Devil Rays starter Ryan Rupe (4-5) was 
the loser. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Orioles 1, Angels 0    	
</P>
<P>
	At Baltimore, Juan Guzman pitched eight scoreless innings as the  
Orioles spoiled Jack McDowell's 1999 debut and handed the Angels 
their eighth straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
	McDowell, activated from the disabled list before the game,  
allowed one run and four hits in 5 2-3 innings. The 1993 Cy Young 
winner, sidelined after undergoing offseason surgery on his right 
elbow and shoulder, was making his first appearance in the majors 
since Sept. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	McDowell (0-1) was outdueled by Guzman (5-8), who lost four of  
his previous five decisions. Harold Baines doubled in the fourth 
and scored the lone run for the Orioles, who have won four straight 
and nine of 11. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Tigers 14, Red Sox 5    	
</P>
<P>
	Five players homered for Detroit and the travails of Boston  
right-hander Tomokazu Ohka continued as the Tigers beat the 
visiting Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohka (0-2), knocked out in the second inning of his major league  
debut against Florida on July 19, gave up three runs in the first. 
Ohka, signed last November from the Japanese professional league, 
yielded seven runs on nine hits in 4 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Santana gave up the next seven runs, including six in the  
sixth -- when the Tigers hit three homers. Karim Garcia, Deivi Cruz, 
Gregg Jefferies, Jason Wood and Luis Polonia also homered for the 
Tigers, while Jose Offerman had a two-run homer for Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit starter Brian Moehler (8-9) benefited from his  
teammates' power show. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Twins 5, Mariners 4    	
</P>
<P>
	Matt Lawton's RBI single in the bottom of the ninth led  
Minnesota to a comeback victory over Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawton's single off Jose Paniagua (6-9) scored pinch-runner  
Jacques Jones from third, as the Twins battled back from a 4-0 
deficit. The Twins rallied for a run in the sixth and three more in 
the seventh to tie the game 4-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Hector Carrasco (1-2) gained the victory after allowing one hit  
in two innings. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Royals 12, Athletics 7    	
</P>
<P>
	Jermaine Dye knocked in three runs with a double in a seven-run  
third inning, and Kansas City rallied to win its seventh straight 
home game. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland, which has an AL-worst 18-31 road record, took a 6-1  
lead in the third on Jason Giambi's grand slam off Mac Suzuki and 
Eric Chavez's RBI double. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Royals went ahead 8-6 in the bottom of the third with  
the help of Dye's big hit. Jeremy Giambi, Jason's younger brother, 
capped the rally with a run-scoring double. 
  	   	
</P>
