<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Equates Self to M. Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASPEN, Colo. (AP) -- President Clinton tried to put a little  
bounce in a couple of political speeches over the weekend by 
telling Democratic supporters Republicans now regard him less as a 
``bad guy'' and more as a Michael Jordan of politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton meant that, in his view, the GOP hopes it can write off  
Clinton as an extraordinary successful Democrat the likes of whom, 
like His Airness, probably won't be seen again soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're now basically saying, 'Oh, well, Bill Clinton is like  
Michael Jordan -- he just jumps higher than the other guys,''' 
Clinton told well-heeled Democrats Saturday at a red-checked 
tablecloth picnic in this chic mountain town. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans, ``after telling everybody for 6 1/2 years what a  
bad guy I was,'' are now looking forward to the time 18 months from 
now when Clinton leaves office, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans figure that at that point, ``he's gone, so we'll  
put them in the cellar again,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speech also included a lengthy list of things Clinton  
considers successes of his tenure -- he cites advances in elementary 
education, a cleaner environment and a booming economy, among other 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton made a similar speech and a similar reference to the  
retired Chicago Bulls great on Friday night, during a fund-raising 
stop in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	He paraphrased Republican thinking this way: ``Clinton's like  
Michael Jordan, he just jumps higher than the other Democrats now 
(but) the natural order of things will reassert itself and we 
Republicans will rule America again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton skipped the Jordan reference when he gave an otherwise  
comparable address later Saturday, and told reporters he is no 
political Air Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	When ``one of my Republican friends'' made the Jordan analogy,  
Clinton said he replied: ``No one in their right mind could compare 
me to Michael Jordan. ... I can't jump four inches.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
