<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Headed to Familiar Terrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG POND, Pa. (AP) -- Tony Stewart is going back home to Indiana  
next month to run for the first time in the Brickyard 400. But he's 
no novice when it comes to racing at the Indianapolis Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	He competed four times in the Indianapolis 500 during his days  
in the Indy Racing League. When asked what he could tell everyone 
about his experience, NASCAR's best rookie and top quipster was 
ready: 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you where to eat and the easiest way to get in and  
out of the race track,'' he said Saturday. ``I'll have them all 
drawn up and ready for you guys at Indianapolis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about a recent test for the Brickyard 400, Stewart said  
things didn't go as well as he would have preferred. But they could 
have been worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I left without hitting the wall,'' he said of his laps around  
the 2 1/2-mile rectangle. ``And you've got four chances to hit that 
wall there instead of two.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who starts 12th Sunday in the Pennsylvania 500, was  
asked just how hard he planned to run in the Brickyard 400 on Aug. 
7. He bemoaned that the difference between the heavy Winston Cup 
cars and light Indy cars will keep him from employing his old IRL 
strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I get to run wide open around there, I'll kill them guys,''  
he said. ``Then we'll have a hell of a celebration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he learned a great deal about the real payoff of racing  
when he began competing in Indiana as an 8-year-old go-kart driver. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you won you always got the good-looking girl in school that  
week,'' he said. ``And the next week, somebody else won, and they 
got the girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	AND THE REST: Rookie Elliott Sadler will have to drop from 40th  
position to the rear of the field on the pace lap Sunday before the 
Pennsylvania 500 because he will be in a backup car. 
</P>
<P>
	Sadler totaled the Wood Brothers' Ford while attempting to  
qualify Saturday at Pocono International Raceway. X-rays on his 
left foot proved negative. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has probably been the worst weekend of racing I've had,''  
said Sadler, who blew two engines during practice Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Shepherd, who lost his chance to race when Joe Falk's car  
failed to qualify, drove the car some for his former team during 
the final practice session Saturday, and he'll stand by in case 
Sadler needs relief Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other car that failed to make the 43-car field was the  
Pontiac of Derrike Cope. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	AND THE WINNER: Blaise Alexander, from nearby Mountoursville,  
Pa., showed plenty of aggression while winning the ARCA Pepsi 200 
on Saturday at Pocono International Raceway. 
</P>
<P>
	He bumped Jeff Finley aside of the 64th of 80 laps, then held on  
to beat Frank Kimmel by nearly a half-second. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he was too happy with me,'' Alexander said of  
Finley. ``But we weren't racing for 25th. We were going for the 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finley wound up fourth.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	PIT STOPS: Stanton Barrett, who will drive Junie Donlavey's Ford  
on Sunday in the Pennsylvania 500, spent part of Saturday working 
on the crew of old friend Barry Owen's car in the ARCA Pepsi 200. 
... Starting at or near the front is advantageous at Pocono 
International Raceway. The winner has come from the first two rows 
in 25 of 43 Pocono NASCAR races. ... Hendrick Motorsports leads all 
teams in victories at Pocono with eight. Jeff Gordon and the late 
Tim Richmond won three times apiece for Hendrick, and Geoff Bodine 
and Terry Labonte once each. ... No one has won consecutively at 
the track since June 1987, when Richmond got the last of his three 
straight victories. ... Despite Bobby Labonte's victory five weeks 
ago in the Pocono 500, the triangle on the mountain has not been a 
good track for Pontiac. The winner has been in a Pontiac only four 
times in 43 races since stock cars began running on the track in 
1974. ... Michael Waltrip is winless in 412 Winston Cup starts. 
Older brother Darrell got the most recent of his 84 career 
victories in 1992, making the Waltrip family 0-for-624 since. ... 
Dave Marcis has gone 457 races since his last victory, in 1982. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
