<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 02:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Begin Post-Elway Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- John Mobley unpacked his belongings and  
brashly shouted, ``Time for No. 3,'' symbolizing the Denver 
Broncos' readiness to pursue their Super Bowl victory No. 3 without 
the services of No. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The post-John Elway era officially began Friday as Denver opened  
training camp at the University of Northern Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Tight end Shannon Sharpe, one of the retired quarterback's  
favorite targets, was so anxious to get to Greeley that he got a 
speeding ticket -- his fourth in 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	It's easy to get pumped up when you've won the last two Super  
Bowls, and no one is conceding there won't be a third straight just 
because Bubby Brister, and not Elway, will be the guy throwing the 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We definitely have to go on,'' Sharpe said. ``I'm not going to  
sit here and try to kid anybody and say that we don't wish that he 
was back, because we do. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bubby now has to prove that he can throw the football, that he  
can beat people. If Bubby can't throw the football, we're in 
trouble. He knows that. We know that. There's no sense in me trying 
to sugarcoat it, but I think Bubby can get the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did last season, guiding the Broncos to five victories when  
Elway was sidelined by injuries. Nobody expects Brister to put up 
Hall of Fame statistics, but there will be no shortage of pressure. 
A crowd of cameras and reporters greeted him as he arrived Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I can deal with it for a year or two and then let  
somebody else take over,'' Brister, 36, said. ``I'm excited about 
it. I'm ready to do some talking with my body instead of my 
mouth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So are his teammates, who throughout the day pulled to the curb  
outside the dorm in luxury sedans and shiny sport-utility trucks to 
unload quilts, pillows and video disc players. 
</P>
<P>
	While his former teammates prepared for training camp, Elway was  
vacationing with his family, far removed from the spotlight he held 
since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	There was an Elway at camp, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I'm filling any void, but it's different,'' said  
John Elway's father, Jack Elway, the team's director of pro 
scouting. ``His time had to come eventually. It's here, and I'm 
sure he doesn't have any reservations that he had to change gears 
and go in another direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterback's absence drew as much attention as his presence  
ever did. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be different for everybody,'' coach Mike  
Shanahan said, ``but his spirit is still here. How competitive John 
was and what he's meant to this organization, it's still in every 
player on this football team. Even though he's gone, his spirit's 
still within us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
