<HEADLINE> Moving Co. Sues Wal-Mart Heiress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- A moving company is taking one of  
America's richest women to court over a $14,000 unpaid bill. 
</P>
<P>
	United Van Lines, which filed the suit here Wednesday, claims  
Wal-Mart heiress Alice Walton refused to pay them for moving 
property from her New York City apartment to a ranch 50 miles west 
of Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walton, the daughter of Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton, is  
disputing the moving bill because some of her belongings were 
damaged, said Jay Allen, a family spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen was not specific, but said some of the items were of  
significant value. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the Missouri-based moving line would not comment  
on the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walton and her mother are the country's richest women, with  
an estimated $16 billion apiece. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
