<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-24 09:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Who Hit King Had Poor Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- Sheriff's investigators continue to  
investigate the accident last month that left horror writer Stephen 
King with several broken bones. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Smith, 42, the driver of a van that struck King on June 19  
along a rural road, maintains he did nothing wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Although authorities filed no charges, they have pointed to a  
list of previous driving offenses against Smith and kept the case 
open. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got the world looking at something we're putting  
together. I think it was in our best interest to go a little bit 
further,'' said Capt. James Miclon of the Oxford County Sheriff's 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who said he was distracted by his pet dog in the van just  
prior to the crash, said the authorities are wasting their time. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing to investigate. I was in an accident that had  
no cause,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	State driving records indicate Smith has several offenses over  
the past decade or so. Among them, convictions for: driving to 
endanger; failing to stop upon the signal of a police officer; 
failing to produce evidence of insurance; operating under the 
influence; and four speeding violations -- two in 1988 and two in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``His record has been poor, and that's cause for concern,'' said  
Maine Secretary of State Dan Gwadosky, who oversees the Bureau of 
Motor Vehicles 
</P>
<P>
	The accident near King's vacation home in North Lovell has  
forced the author to undergo five operations to set the broken 
bones in his right leg and hip. 
</P>
<P>
	He also suffered broken ribs, a punctured lung and a skull  
laceration in the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	While King is moving around his home in a wheelchair under  
round-the-clock nursing supervision, rehabilitation has put his 
writing on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he's writing, he doesn't want any interference,'' said  
his secretary, Julie Eugley. ``He knows that the physical therapy 
part of it is more important than the writing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
