<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Announces Updated Air Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore tried Saturday to breathe  
fresh air into the nation's 2-decade-old air quality index system, 
saying the Environmental Protection Agency is planning to give more 
detailed health warnings so vulnerable people can protect 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	He made the announcement at the groundbreaking for a children's  
hospital in the Bronx. 
</P>
<P>
	A new category added to the air quality index will bring relief  
to 6 million children with asthma and others with respiratory 
conditions, Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new index will provide specific, more detailed  
information, included warnings for those with special health 
conditions such as asthma,'' the vice president added. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said local forecasters would deliver a ``uniform, clear,  
understandable measure of daily air quality and the health risks 
associated with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The new air quality index is a critical tool Americans need to  
protect their health,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many local weather forecasters since 1976 have reported daily on  
the Air Quality Index, which measures the health effects of air 
pollution. Pollution measurements are divided into ranges, and a 
health advisory is given based on the day's ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration said it wanted changes to the index  
in part because people are not adequately told how to protect 
themselves on days when the air can adversely affect their health. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised model is meant to provide a consistent format for  
weather forecasters to explain when air pollution poses a health 
risk and what precautions can be taken. The new index measures five 
major air pollutants: smog, soot, sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide 
and nitrogen dioxide. 
</P>
<P>
	Threats to health from unsafe levels of any or all of these  
pollutants can trigger a health protection warning for that day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
