<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Decathlete Gets Ultimatum From Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Decathlete Chris Huffins' wife,  
Monique, is putting a lot of pressure on him at the Pan American 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said, `If you don't come home with the gold, don't come  
home,''' Huffins said with a laugh Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning should be no problem for Huffins, the world's  
fifth-ranked decathlete. He is an overwhelming favorite against a 
weak field of four in the 10-event, two-day competition that began 
today at the University of Manitoba. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor should he have any difficulty smashing the Pan Am Games  
record of 8,078 points by American Bob Coffman in 1979. Huffins has 
a career-best of 8,694 last year in the USA Championships at New 
Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomas Dvorak of the Czech Republic holds the world record of  
8,994, set earlier this month at Prague, a performance Huffins 
closely tracked on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``After four events, I said to my wife, `He's going to break the  
world record,''' Huffins said. ``Then, after nine events, I said he 
was going to break 9,000 points. I'm glad he just missed because I 
want to be the first over 9,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huffins will get his shot at Dvorak and the world record next  
month in the world championships at Seville, Spain, where the heat 
and humidity are expected to take a heavy toll on the athletes. 
Huffins thinks the adverse weather, with the temperature usually 
over 100 degrees in the summer, will be to his benefit, because he 
is used to training in warm climates. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't convince me there's any place hotter than New  
Orleans,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Heat means fluids. While everyone else in Seville will be  
complaining about the heat, I won't. My best three marks have been 
in temperatures over 90 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it's cold and rainy, that's a big problem, because you  
don't have to deal with that at home when you're training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This will be Huffins' final tuneup before the worlds, and he  
wants to make a strong impression. He would rather be competing 
than practicing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't sit at home and train for eight weeks for one meet,''  
he said. ``In practice, I can get to competition readiness and then 
get stale. I can only match by PRs (personal records) so many times 
in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to put up a good mark here. I would like to have the  
Pan Am Games record after nine events. That's no disrespect to the 
other decathletes. When I compete, it's me against the scoring 
tables.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A solid performance would make Huffins, the two-time U.S.  
champion, a strong contender to dethrone Dvorak as world champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have beaten Dvorak more than once,'' Huffins said. ``After  
the (1997) world championships, he got trounced by me at Talence 
(France). I had something people don't often get, and that's a 
chance at redemption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the 1997 worlds in Athens, Huffins led through seven events,  
then fouled three times in the javelin, killing his chance for the 
gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Huffins is a consummate student of track and field. He trains up  
to 60 hours a week, participates in a track and field fantasy 
league and has more than 200 videotapes of various meets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be the best decathlete that ever lived,'' he said.  
``World's greatest athlete is probably the most glamorous title on 
the planet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Huffins completes the testing decathlon in Winnipeg, he  
might have an added job -- running on the U.S. 400-meter relay team. 
</P>
<P>
	Men's coach Ralph Lindeman of the Air Force Academy said he  
might draft Huffins for the relay because of a shortage of quality 
sprinters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why shouldn't we use a guy who can run 10.20?'' Lindeman said.  
</P>
<P>
	The 400 relay final is Friday, meaning Huffins would have to  
stay an extra five days. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a good chance I'm running,'' Huffins said, ``much to  
my wife's chagrin. My wife told me if I stay, I better run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another ultimatum.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
