<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in Naturalist's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A motel maintenance man wanted for  
questioning in connection with the beheading death of a Yosemite 
National Park naturalist was arrested early today, according to a 
radio report. 
</P>
<P>
	KFBK radio reported that Cary Stayner, 38, was arrested in  
Wilton, Calif., southeast of Sacramento. Further details were not 
immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Sacramento County sheriff's officials would not confirm the  
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner disappeared after being interviewed Thursday by FBI  
agents, the San Francisco Chronicle reported. He works as a 
handyman at the Cedar Lodge in El Portal, about four miles from 
where the woman's body was found Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangers found the 26-year-old woman's body along a stream a few  
hundred yards from the park housing she shared with a man and 
woman, who were away at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	A park official who spoke on the condition of anonymity told The  
Associated Press the woman had been decapitated. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Brian Muller of the Mariposa County Sheriff's Department  
told the Chronicle on Friday that authorities were searching for 
Stayner and that sheriff's officials were to notify the FBI and 
Yosemite park police if he was found. 
</P>
<P>
	The victim was initially reported missing by a friend she was  
due to visit in Sausalito, just north of San Francisco. Her loaded 
car was found outside her quarters, ready for the trip. The friend 
called Sausalito police to file the missing-persons report. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agent James Maddock said ``a large, very large'' area was  
carefully searched Friday for clues. The search was to continue 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities do not believe the woman's death is related to those  
of three sightseers, who were last seen at the Cedar Lodge a month 
before their bodies were found in March, Maddock said. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman worked at the Yosemite Institute, a nonprofit group  
that runs education programs through a partnership with the park 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was one of the finest naturalists and science teachers I  
ever met,'' said John Carlstroem, executive director of the 
Headlands Institute, the Yosemite Institute's sister campus. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
