<HEADLINE> Text of Eulogy for Lauren Bessette </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Text of the eulogy given by Dr. Jack Messina during the memorial  
service for Lauren Bessette. He is her uncle, the brother of her 
mother, Ann Freeman. 

</P>
<P>
	Lauren Bessette was born on Nov. 5, 1964, followed three minutes  
later by her twin sister, Lisa. Fifteen months later, Carolyn 
Bessette entered the world. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 16, 1999, two of these remarkable women, along with  
Carolyn's beloved husband, John Kennedy, unexpectedly left us. 
Their departure has left an enormous void in all our lives and has 
touched the lives of millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Carolyn and John were meaningfully eulogized by Hamilton  
South and Senator Ted Kennedy at yesterday's memorial service. It 
was no easy task for them to reflect on the lives of Carolyn and 
John within a limited time frame, and I find it equally daunting to 
share with you in the short time we have together the essence of my 
niece, Lauren, an enormously complex woman whom we all loved. 
</P>
<P>
	As I began to think of what I would say, it became clear that  
this could not be accomplished from just my perspective. Lauren's 
character and personality was so rich, vibrant and multifaceted 
that I turned to other family members to share their thoughts and 
feelings. From the children, Kristin, Matthew, Courtney, Kyle and 
the four Floyd 'Killer Bees' -- Brittney, Bobby, Billy and Buddy -- 
we collected these words'': 
</P>
<P>
	She fit into our kid world -- she was more like a friend and a  
sister than a grown-up. She was really fun. We remember the day she 
played miniature golf in the back yard in her pajamas and high 
heels. She knew so much about so many things and was always 
teaching us things.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Her goddaughter told me she is saving every beautiful thing  
Lauren ever gave her so she can pass them on to her children. We 
are comforted in knowing that Lauren is still with the children in 
memory and spirit. 
</P>
<P>
	In moving on to her friends, I learned more about Lauren. They  
described her as someone always there to find that piece of elusive 
information that was wanted so desperately, to introduce them to 
the exact person they needed in their lives to say a good word when 
it was really needed and to always boost them up when things were 
tough. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren had a far-reaching spiritual side. She honored the  
beliefs of many religious heritages and was not above consulting 
Chinese fortunetellers. From a packet of angel cards recently given 
to her, a friend selected a few cards that captured the spirit and 
colors of Lauren -- strength, compassion, tenderness, adventure, 
beauty, courage, responsibility, power, abundance, enthusiasm, 
grace and love. 
</P>
<P>
	A close friend shared a few e-mail communications he had  
received from Lauren, and one so reflected her sense of humor that 
I felt compelled to share it. To put it mildly, Lauren was never 
much of a sports fan. Until recently, she had never attended a 
professional sporting event. 
</P>
<P>
	However, after attending her first prize fight, in typical  
Lauren fashion, she began to enthusiastically embrace all 
professional sports. She e-mailed the following: `I am now 
considering to be such an avid sports fan that the invitations just 
keep rolling in. Off to the Knicks game tonight and I can only 
imagine what tomorrow will bring. I am the envy of my male 
colleagues, all of who are extremely bitter, which naturally 
enhances my enjoyment of these events. Thanks again to the 
introduction to boxing.' Lauren's personality to a T. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren was an adoring grandchild. Her love for her Nana knew no  
bounds. I know she'll continue to keep a protective eye out for 
her. Lauren's mother, my sister Ann, reflected on the light and joy 
her daughter brought into her life. She was pleased with what 
Lauren accomplished professionally, but she was most proud of who 
she was and who she was becoming. She loved Lauren's sense of 
personal entitlement, the view she held of the world as her own and 
her ability to convince the world this was true. 
</P>
<P>
	To me, Lauren was fascinating as all the Bessette woman are and  
were. She was breathtakingly intelligent. Her intellect and sense 
of aesthetics allowed her to appreciate art, literature, opera, 
economics and world events. Everything was interesting to her. It 
was a marvel to be around her and see if you could catch up and 
keep up. Conversation with her was lightning-quick, broad-based, 
often irreverent, filled with repartee and always witty. Just 
listening to her I felt a sense of pride, a hope in the future 
because of our young people and maybe just a little bit old. 
</P>
<P>
	I can still see Lauren, tall and gracefully talking with those  
adorably quirky hand gestures. I see her tossing that long shiny 
hair and hear her laughter. I sense her vitality and her strength 
and her love. We shall miss her. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite our losses, our family's grateful to have Lisa with us.  
Like my other two nieces, she possesses the gifts of intelligence, 
wit, compassion and drive. We cherish her for those qualities that 
remind us of Lauren and Carolyn, but in particular for those that 
make her a unique and special individual in her own right. 
</P>
<P>
	If the events of these past eight days have taught us anything,  
it is to honor the moment. Cherish those around you. Try to find a 
balance between work and family. Contribute something to your 
community and above all, share the love you feel for others each 
and every day. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauren loved opera, but her taste in music was eclectic. Amongst  
her favorite songs was ``She's a Rainbow'' by Mick Jagger. I now 
know why. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
