<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Public Bids JFK Jr. Final Goodbye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Like thousands of others who waited outside the  
private memorial mass for John F. Kennedy Jr. and Carolyn Bessette 
Kennedy, Linda Simidian never met the couple. 
</P>
<P>
	``Which is why this is all so surreal,'' said Simidian, 37. ``I  
didn't know him. So why do I care so much that he's gone?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She didn't have an answer; nor did many others. They just wanted  
the chance to say a final goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to be here today to support the family in their grief  
and to let them know they're not alone,'' said a tearful Julia 
Clegg Sansevere, 43, said Friday. She held a sign that read: 
``John, Carolyn and Lauren, Rest in peace with God in heaven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sansevere was a girl in Texas when President John F. Kennedy was  
killed. ``I felt like I lost a father, and now I've lost a 
brother,'' she cried. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy, 38, his wife, 33, and her sister, Lauren Bessette, 34,  
died July 16 when the single-engine plane Kennedy piloted crashed 
into the Atlantic off Martha's Vineyard. Their cremated remains 
were committed to the ocean Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's memorial mass was by invitation only, but people from  
around the world flocked to Manhattan's Upper East Side for their 
own sense of closure and in support of the Kennedy family, to which 
they all felt connected. 
</P>
<P>
	There was the Queens mother who mourned the family JFK Jr. and  
his wife would never have; the nanny who once said hello to 
Jacqueline Onassis on a Manhattan street; the Harlem woman who 
shook hands more than three decades ago with Robert F. Kennedy; and 
Ms. Simidian, who had a poster of a young JFK Jr. in her college 
dorm room. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just a couple of years older than me and I had a real  
crush on him,'' said Ms. Simidian, who came with her 5-year-old 
niece to the small gothic Church of St. Thomas More, where the mass 
was held. 
</P>
<P>
	Janet Clark and her dog, Cocoa, came to honor Kennedy's uncle,  
Robert F. Kennedy, whose hand she shook during a campaign swing 
through Harlem 31 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a good dude, a good guy,'' Clark said. ``He came to  
Harlem before anyone else and I've followed the Kennedys ever 
since.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spectators were kept blocks from the church and couldn't see  
much. But that didn't seem to matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not here to see anyone,'' said Jessica Rigul, 39, of  
Queens, who arrived hours before the service began. ``I just want 
to stay until I feel some peace inside of me for this tragedy. ... 
Here we are the same age, and I'm dropping my daughter off at 
summer school; he didn't even get the chance to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the week since his death, thousands have filed past the  
Kennedys loft apartment, leaving bouquets of flowers, poems, 
stuffed animals, heartbreaking letters and candles. A local charity 
picked up three vanloads and ``that didn't even touch the surface,' 
said Leslye Schneider, executive director of Variety-The Children's 
Charity. 
</P>
<P>
	A much smaller memorial appeared outside the church where the  
private service was held. A few summer bouquets of violet, red and 
yellow flowers, and a purple balloon, were left in a decorative 
railing about a half block away. 
</P>
<P>
	Tere Perez, who carried a homemade vase decorated with pictures  
of Kennedy, felt she had a real Kennedy connection. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw him playing football in Central Park a couple of times  
and once said hello to Mrs. Onassis on a Manhattan street. 
</P>
<P>
	``She smiled and waved at me,'' the 43-year-old nanny recalled.  
``This is just my way of paying my respects.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
