<HEADLINE> Reggae, Eulogies for JFK. Jr. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The memorial Mass for John F. Kennedy Jr. and  
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy included an eclectic mix of readings and 
music, ranging from Shakespeare to a reggae anthem. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters were not admitted, but mourners said the ceremony, at  
the Church of St. Thomas More in Manhattan, opened with the hymn 
``All Creatures of our God and King.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other songs performed by the O Freedom Gospel Choir included  
``On Eagle's Wings,'' ``Forever Young'' and a rendition of ``Swing 
Low, Sweet Chariot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hip-hop artist Wyclef Jean sang the reggae anthem ``Many Rivers  
to Cross.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kennedy's mother, Ann Freeman, read from Henry Scott  
Holland's meditation ``Facts of Faith.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though it was not known which part she read, the piece includes  
this passage: ``Death is nothing at all. It does not count. I have 
only slipped away into the next room. Nothing has happened. 
Everything remains exactly as it was. I am, and you are, and the 
old life that we lived so fondly together is untouched, unchanged. 
... I am but waiting for you, for an interval, somewhere very near, 
just around the corner. All is well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's sister, Caroline Kennedy, read from Act IV, Scene 1 of  
Shakespeare's ``The Tempest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mass was celebrated by the Rev. Charles J. O'Byrne, the Rev.  
John Boehning and Monsignor George F. Bardes. O'Byrne married JFK 
Jr. and Carolyn in 1996 at a clandestine ceremony off the coast of 
Georgia and presided over their burial at sea Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
